column3: Compounds that contain at least carbon atom, excluding isocyanide/cyanide and their non-hydrocarbyl derivatives, thiophosgene, carbon diselenide, carbon monosulfide, carbon disulfide, carbon subsulfide, carbon monoxide, carbon trioxide, Carbon suboxide, and dicarbon monoxide.
Compounds that do not contain a C atom.
Compounds containing a ring with least one carbon atom and one non-carbon atom.
Organic compounds containing a heptane ring in which one carbon atom is replaced by a sulfur atom.
Organic compounds containing a carbon-sulfur bond.
Compounds with a structure based on the 2,7,-tricarboxy-1H-pyrrolo[2,3-f ]quinoline-4,5-dione. Pyrroloquinoline Quinones usually bear a carboxylic acid group at the C-2, C-7 and C-9 positions.

Organic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to an oxazoline ring. Oxazoline is five-membered unsaturated ring with a nitrogen atom and an oxygen atom at the 1- and 3-position, respectively. Additionally, it contains two double bonds.
Derivatives of oxoacids RnE(=O)OH in which the hydroxy group is replaced by an amino group and the oxo group is replaced by =NR. Amidines include carboxamidines, sulfinamidines and phosphinamidines.

Diterpenoids with a structure based a cembrane skeleton, which is characterized by the presence of an isopropyl group at C-1 and by three symmetrically disposed methyl groups a the t C-4, -8 and -12 positions.
S-Oxides of thioaldehydes and thioketones.
S,S-Dioxides of thioaldehydes and thioketones, R2C=SO2.
Monosaccharides, disaccharides, oligosaccharides, polysaccharides, and their derivatives.
Fatty acids and their derivatives, and substances related biosynthetically or functionally to these compounds.
Organic compounds containing an amino acid or a peptide backbone, or derivatives thereof.
Compounds containing a phenylbutylamine moiety, which consists of a phenyl group substituted at the fourth carbon by an butan-1-amine.
Compounds containing a dibenzofuran moiety, which consists of two benzene rings fused to a central furan ring.

Compounds in which one carbon atom has double bonds with each of its two adjacent carbon centers. The definition includes both the hydrocarbon molecules and their derivatives obtained by substitution.
Unsaturated monocyclic hydrocarbons having one endocyclic double bond.
Organic compounds containing a system of three linearly fused benzene rings.
Compounds containing a dibenzocycloheptene moiety, which consists of two benzene rings connected by a cycloheptene ring.
Compounds containing a fluorene moiety, which consists of two benzene rings connected through either a cyclopentane, cyclopentene, or cyclopenta-1,3-diene.
Compounds containing an indene moiety(which consists of a cyclopentadiene fused to a benzene ring), or a isoindene moiety (which consists of a cyclopentadiene fused to cyclohexadiene ring).
Compounds containing a naphthacene moiety, which is a polyaromatic hydrocarbon made of four linearly fused benzene rings.
Compounds containing a naphthalene moiety, which consists of two fused benzene rings.
Compounds containing a pentacene moiety, which is consists of five linearly fused benzene rings.
Polycyclic compounds containing a phenanthrene moiety, which is a tricyclic aromatic compound with three non-linearly fused benzene.
Purine Ribonucleotides in which the ribose sugar esterified with one phosphate group attached to each of two different hydroxy groups on the sugar, usually at positions 2', 3', or 5'.
Compounds containing an indane moiety, which consists of a cyclopentane fused to a benzene ring.

Compounds containing a pyridoxal moiety, which consists of a pyridine ring substituted at positions 2,3,4, and 5 by a methyl group, a hydroxyl group, a carbaldehyde group, and a hydroxymethyl group, respectively.
Organic aromatic compounds containing a cinnamlaldehyde moiety, consisting of a benzene and an aldehyde group to form 3-phenylprop-2-enal.
Eicosanoic acids with an attached hydroxyl group and three CC double bonds.
Organic compounds containing a sulfonamide group that is S-linked to a benzene ring.
Organic compounds containing a sulfonic acid or a derivative thereof that is linked to a benzene ring.
Organic compounds containing the phenylmethanol substructure.
Benzoic acids carrying a sulfonyl group on the benzene ring.
Aromatic compounds containing a halogen atom linked to a benzene ring.
Compounds containing a nitrobenzene moiety, which consists of a benzene ring with a carbon bearing a nitro group.
Organic compounds containing an ethenylbenzene moiety.
Organic aromatic compounds containing a sulfanilide moiety, with the general structure RS(=O)(=O)NC1=CC=CC=C1.
Organic compounds containing a sulfamic acid moiety or a derivative, with the general structure R1N(R2)S(=O)2OR3  (R1,R2,R3=H, alkyl, aryl).
Compounds containing an indane ring bearing two ketone groups.
Organic compounds containing to benzene rings linked together by a C-C bond.
Cyclic aromatic compounds containing a diphenhydramine moiety, which consists of a diphenylmethoxyl group like to an ethyldimethylamine to form [2-(diphenylmethoxy)ethyl]dimethylamine.
Organic compounds containing a biphenyl attached to a benzimidazole. A carbon atom of the biphenyl moiety is boned to a carbon or the nitrogen atom of the benzimidazole moiety.
Organic compounds containing a biphenyl attached to a tetrazole. A carbon atom of the biphenyl moiety is boned to a carbon or the nitrogen atom of the tetrazole moiety.
Compounds containing a phenylpropene moiety, which consists of a propene substituent bound to a phenyl group.
Eicosanoic acids with an attached hydroxyl group and four CC double bonds.
Tetralin lignans in which the benzene moiety of the tetralin skeleton is fused to a 1,3-dioxolane and the cyclohexane is fused to a butyrolactone (pyrrolidin-2-one).
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing a tetralin moiety, which consists of a benzene fused to a cyclohexane.
Compounds containing a tametraline moiety, which consists of a tetrahydronaphthalene linked to a phenyl group to form N-methyl-4-phenyl-1,2,3,4-tetrahydronaphthalen-1-amine skeleton.
Cyclic esters of hydroxy carboxylic acids, containing a 1-oxacycloalkan-2-one structure, or analogues having unsaturation or heteroatoms replacing one or more carbon atoms of the ring.
Monoterpenoids containing at least one aromatic ring.
Organic compounds containing a biphenyl moiety substituted at one or more positions by a bromine atom.
Organic compounds containing an amino group attached to a quinoline ring system.
Organic compounds containing an isoquinoline to which a benzyl group is attached.
Compounds containing a dibenzothiazepine moiety, which consists of two benzene connected by a thiazepine ring.
Compounds containing a quinoline moiety which bears a ketone group.
Compounds containing a quinoline moiety bearing a hydroxyl group.
Polycyclic compounds with a four-ring skeleton with three condensed six-member rings forming a partially hydrogenated phenanthrene moiety, one of which is aromatic while the two others are alicyclic.

Aromatic compounds containing Aromatic compounds containing a cinnamic acid moiety (or a derivative thereof) hydroxylated at the C2 (ortho-), C3 (meta-), or C4 (para-) carbon atom of the benzene ring.
Amino acids in which the amino group is attached to the carbon atom immediately adjacent to the carboxylate group (alpha carbon), or a derivative thereof.
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing an indole fused to a quinoline.
Sulfobenzoic acid carrying the sulfonyl group at the 2-position of the benzene group.
Compounds containing a nitrate ester functional group, with the general structure RON+(=O)O, (R cannot be a hydrogen).

Cyclic amides of amino carboxylic acids, having a 1-azacycloalkan-2-one structure, or analogues having unsaturation or heteroatoms replacing one or more carbon atoms of the ring.  They are nitrogen analogues (the a nitrogen atom replacing the o atom of the cyclic carboxylic acid group ) of the naturally occurring macrolides.
Organic compounds containing an arsacyclopentadiene ring (a five member ring with one arsenic atom, four carbon atoms, and two double bonds).

Compounds containing an oxazepine moiety, which consists of an unsaturated aliphatic seven-member ring with one oxygen atom, a nitrogen atom, and five carbon atoms. Isomers  of oxazepine include 1,2-oxazepine, 1,3-oxazepine,and 1,4-oxazepine.
Compounds containing a pyrazine ring, which is a six-member aromatic heterocycle, that consists of two nitrogen atoms (at positions 1 and 4) and four carbon atoms.
Heterocyclic compounds containing a seven-member aromatic ring with five carbon atoms, one sulfur atom, and one nitrogen atom.
Organic compounds containing an unsaturated seven-member heterocycle with one nitrogen atom replacing a carbon atom.
Compounds containing an oxetane ring, which is a four-member saturated aliphatic ring with an oxygen, and three carbon atoms.

Organic compounds containing a seven-member heterocyclic moiety with five nitrogen atoms, and two nitrogen atoms at positions 1 and 2 (1,2-Diazepines), 1 and 3 (1,3-Diazepines), or 1 and 4 (1,4-Diazepines).
Compounds containing a dibenzodiazepine moiety, which consists of two benzene connected by diazepine ring.
Compounds containing an oxetene ring, which is a four-member unsaturated aliphatic ring with an oxygen, three carbon atoms, and one CC double bond.
Compounds containing a pyridazine ring, which is a six-member aromatic ring containing two nitrogen atoms at positions 1 and 2, and four carbon atoms.
Compounds containing a pyrimidne ring, which is a six-member aromatic heterocycle which consists of two nitrogen atoms (at positions 1 and 3) and four carbon atoms.
Compounds containing a furan ring, which is a five-member aromatic ring with one oxygen atom, four carbon atoms.
Compounds containing a benzene ring which bears a carboxyl group (or a derivative thereof) and a sulfhydryl functional group at positions 1 and 2, respectively.
Compounds containing an imidazole ring, which is an aromatic five-member ring with two nitrogen atoms at positions 1 and 3, and three carbon atoms.

Organic compounds containing an imidazoline ring, which is an unsaturated ring (derived from imidazole) with two nitrogen atoms at positions 1 and 3 respectively, and containing only one CN double bond.
Compounds containing an indazole, which is structurally characterized by a pyrazole fused to a benzene.

Heterocyclic organic compounds containing an isoxazole moiety, with a structure characterized by a five-member aromatic ring with one oxygen atom and one nitrogen atom at ring positions 1 and 2, respectively.

Compounds containing an oxazine moiety, which consists of an unsaturated aliphatic six-member ring with one oxygen atom, a nitrogen atom, four carbon atoms, and two double bonds. Isomers  of oxaphospholane include 1,2-oxazine, 1,3-oxazine, and 1,4-oxazine.
Compounds containing an oxazole ring, which is a five-membered aromatic heterocycle with one  oxygen, one nitrogen, and three carbon atoms. Isomers include 1,2-oxazole and 1,3-oxazole.
Organic compounds containing 1,3-oxazoline, a five-membered ring with a nitrogen and an oxygen atoms at the 1- and 3-position, respectively. Additionally, it contains two double bonds.
Compounds containing a phosphinine ring, which is a benzene derivative where a carbon ring is replaced by a phosphorus atom.
Compounds containing a pyran ring, which is a six-member heterocyclic, non-aromatic ring with five carbon atoms, one oxygen atom and  two ring double bonds.
Compounds containing a pyrazole ring, which is a five-member aromatic ring with two nitrogen atoms (at positions 1 and 2) and three carbon atoms.
Compounds containing a pyrazoline ring, which is a five-member saturated aliphatic ring with two nitrogen atoms (at positions 1 and 2) and three carbon atoms.
Compounds containing a pyridine ring, which is a six-member aromatic heterocycle which consists of one nitrogen atom and five carbon atoms.
Compounds containing a pyrrole ring, which is a five-member aromatic heterocycle with one nitrogen atom and four carbon atoms.
Compounds containing a pyrroline ring, which is a five-member unsaturated aliphatic ring with one nitrogen atom and four carbon atoms.
Organic compounds containing a tetrazine ring, which is a six-membered aromatic heterocycle made up of four nitrogen atoms and a two carbon atoms.
Cyclic organic compounds containing a thiadiazole ring, which is a five-membered aromatic heterocycle made up of one sulfur atom and two nitrogen atoms.
Heterocyclic compounds containing an aliphatic unsaturated six-member ring with four carbon atoms, one sulfur atom, and one nitrogen. Isomers include 1,2-thiazines, 1,3-thiazines, and 1,4-thiazines.
Heterocyclic compounds containing a five-member aromatic ring made up of one sulfur atom, one nitrogen, and three carbon atoms.
Heterocyclic compounds containing an unsaturated seven-member heterocycle, with six carbon atoms and one sulfur atom.
Compounds containing a five-membered aromatic moiety made up of one sulfur atom and four carbon atoms.
Compounds containing a triazine ring, which is a heterocyclic ring, similar to the six-member benzene ring but with three carbons replaced by nitrogen atoms.
Compounds containing  a five-member aromatic ring of two carbon atoms and three nitrogen atoms.

Polycyclic compounds containing a phenanthridine moiety, which is a tricyclic system with two benzene rings joined by a pyridine forming a non-linear skeleton. Hydrogenated derivatives are also included.
Sesquiterpenoids with a structure based on the eudesmane skeleton.
Organic compounds containing a saturated four-member heterocycle where one nitrogen atom replaces a carbon atom.
Organic compounds containing a saturated three-member heterocycle with one amino group and two methylene groups.
Organic compounds containing an unsaturated three-member heterocycle with one amino group and a double bond.
Compounds containing a dioxolane ring, which is a five-membered saturated ring of two oxygen atoms and three carbon atoms. The dioxolanes are divided in 1,2-dioxolanes, and 1,3-dioxolanes.

Compounds containing an oxathiolane moiety, which consists of a saturated aliphatic five-member ring with one oxygen atom, a sulfur atom, and three carbon atoms. Isomers  of oxaphospholane include meta-oxathiolane, and ortho-oxathiolane.

Compounds containing an oxazinane moiety, which consists of a saturated aliphatic six-member ring with one oxygen atom, a nitrogen atom, and four carbon atoms. Isomers  of oxaphospholane include 1,2-oxazinane, 1,3-oxazinane, and 1,4-oxazinane.
Compounds containing an oxazolidine moiety, which consists of a saturated aliphatic five-member ring with one oxygen atom, one nitrogen, three carbon atoms, and two double bonds.
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing a pteridine moiety, which consists of a pyrimidine fused to a pyrazine ring to form  pyrimido(4,5-b)pyrazine.
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing a pterin moiety, which consist of a pteridine ring bearing a ketone and an amine group to form 2-aminopteridin-4(3H)-one.
Organic compounds containing a tetrazole ring, which is a five-member aromatic heterocycle made up of four nitrogen atoms and a one carbon atom.
Compounds comprising the hydrazine functional group, with the general formula R1R2NNR3R4.
Compounds containing a phenylhydrazide moiety, which consists of a hydrazide substituent attached to a phenyl group.

Organic compounds containing the semicarbazide functional group with the general structure R1(N)R2NR3C(=O)N(R4)R5 (R1-R5=H, alkyl, aryl), a derivative of urea, where the amine group on one side has been replace by a hydrazine group.
Organic compounds containing the semicarbazone functional group, with the general structure R2C=NNHC(=O)NH2.
Compounds containing an N-Alkylidene derivative of hydrazine. They have the generic structure RNN=C(R')R\" (R,R',R\"= H or organyl group).
Compounds containing an imine functional group, with the general structure RN=CR2 (R = H, hydrocarbyl).

Organic compounds  in which a carbonyl group is bonded to two carbon atoms R2C=O (neither R may be a hydrogen atom). Ketones that have one or more alpha-hydrogen atoms undergo keto-enol tautomerization, the tautomer being an enol.
Organic compounds containing the acetophenone structure.
Organic compounds containing a ketone attached to two phenyl groups.

Compounds in which the oxygen of a ketone has been replaced by divalent sulfur R2C=S ( R not H ). Thioketones that have an alpha-hydrogen interconvert with Thioenols. Moreover, they interconvert with thioaldehydes.
Ketones containing a carboxylic acid, and an amine group attached to the alpha carbon atom relative to C=O group.

Organic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to a pyran ring. Pyran a six-membered heterocyclic, non-aromatic ring, made up of five carbon atoms and one oxygen atom and containing two double bonds.
Organic compounds containing the aldehyde functional group.

Organic compounds containing a cyclohexene or cyclohexadiene ring that bears a methylidene group and a ketone group. Isomers include m-quinomethane (6-methylidenecyclohex-2-en-1-one), o-quinomethane (5-methylidenecyclohex-2-en-1-one), and p-quinomethane (4-methylidenecyclohexa-2,5-dien-1-one).
Compounds bearing the group N3, viz. -N=N+=N-; usually attached to carbon, e.g. PhN3 phenyl azide or azidobenzene.
Heteropolycyclic compounds with a structure containing isoindole, a benzo-fused pyrrole.
Organic compounds containing the alkyl aryl ether functional group with the generic formula R-O-R' , where R is an alkyl group and R' is an aryl group.
Organic compounds in which at least one hydroxyl functional group (-OH) is bound to a carbon atom, usually connected to other carbon or hydrogen atoms.
Organic compounds containing a spirodecane moiety with at least one nitrogen atom.
Compounds containing the enediol functional group, with the formula HO(R)C=C(R')OH.
Compounds containing the enol functional group, with the structure HO(R)C=CR'. Ketones that have one or more alpha-hydrogen atoms undergo keto-enol tautomerization, the tautomer being an enol.
Carbonyl compounds with the generic formula O=C(R)C(H)C(R')=O, where R and R' can be any group.
Compounds containing a phenol moiety, which is a benzene bearing a hydroxyl group.
Compounds containing a 1,2-benzenediol moiety.
Compounds containing a hydroquinone moiety, which consists of a benzene ring with a hydroxyl groups at positions 1 and 4.
Compounds containing a resorcinol moiety, which is a benzene ring bearing two hydroxyl groups at positions 1 and 3.
Organic compounds containing a methoxybenzene or a derivative thereof.
Compounds containing a hydroxyethyl group attached to the C4 carbon of a phenol group.
Organic compounds containing an amino group attached to a phenol.
Compounds containing a nitrophenol moiety, which consists of a benzene ring bearing both a hydroxyl group and a nitro group on two different ring carbon atoms.
Compounds structurally characterized by the presence of a carbohydrate moiety glycosidically linked to the stilbene skeleton.

Methylenediphenols, HOC6H4CH2C6H4OH, commonly p,p-methylenediphenol, and their substitution products (generally derived from condensation of two equivalent amounts of a phenol with an aldehyde or ketone).
Compounds containing a benzopyran-4-one moiety.
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing a 1-benzopyran moiety with a ketone group at the C2 carbon atom (1-benzopyran-2-one).
Organic compounds containing a sugar linked to a chain through N-acyl group.
Organic compounds containing a lactone ring of at least twelve members.
Compounds containing a dithiazole moiety, which consists of an unsaturated five-member ring containing two carbon atoms, one nitrogen atom, and two sulfur atoms.
Difuranocoumarin derivatives in which the coumarin is fused to either a cyclopentenone (difurocoumarocyclopentenone series) or a lactone (difurocoumarolactone series).
Compounds containing a dibenzoxazepine moiety, which consists of two benzene connected by an oxazepine ring.
Organic compounds containing either anthracene-9,10-quinone, 1,4-anthraquinone, or 1,2-anthraquinone.
M-quinones that carry an imine group.
Compounds containing a naphthohydroquinone moiety, which consists of a benzene ring linearly fused to a bezene-1,4-dione (quinone).
Compounds containing a pentacenequinone moiety, which consists of five linearly fused benzene ring, with at least one bearing two ketones.
Polyaromatic hydrocarbon derivatives containing a tetracyclic cycle made up of four linearly fused benzene rings, one of which bears two ketone groups at position 1 and 4.
Organic compounds containing a ketone group is attached to the adamantane (tricyclo[3.3.1.1]decane) ring.
Organic compounds containing a functional group consisting of the formula RN=C=NR.
Organic compounds comprising the hydroxylamine functional group, with the general structure R1ON(R2)R3 (R1,R3=H, organyl; R2 = organyl).
Compounds containing a cyclic ether with three ring atoms(one oxygen and two carbon atoms).

Compounds containing a lactam ring, which is a cyclic amide of amino carboxylic acids, having a 1-azacycloalkan-2-one structure (or an analogue having unsaturation or heteroatoms replacing one or more carbon atoms of the ring).

Macrolides consisting of a 16-member lactone ring conjugated at the carbon 16 with a 1-(2-methyl-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)prop-1-en-2-yl group. Some epothilone analogues containing a lactam ring instead of the lactone ring.
Organic compounds containing a four-member lactam (a cyclic amide).
Cyclic amides of caproic acid. Caproic acid is the carboxylic acid derived from hexane with the general formula C5H11COOH.
Cyclic organic compounds containing a piperidin-2-one moiety.
Organic compounds containing a gamma-lactam moiety, which consists of a five-member lactam ring.
Cyclic thioamides, obtained by replacing the oxygen atom from a lactam ring with sulfur.
Beta-lactam derivatives in which the beta-lactam ring shares the nitrogen atom with a pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid.
Organic compounds containing the 5-thia-1-azabicyclo[4.2.0]oct-2-en-8-one nucleus.
Organic compounds containing a 4-oxa-1-azabicyclo[3.2.0]heptan-7-one moiety. Clavams are similar to penams, but with an oxygen substituted for the sulfur in the penam skeleton.
Compounds comprising beta-lactam ring is alone and not fused to another ring.
Organic compounds containing the oxacepehem skeleton, which is similar to a cephem, but with oxygen substituted for the sulfur.
Organic heterocyclic compounds containing the 4-thia-1-azabicyclo[3.2.0]heptan-7-one structure.
Compounds containing a 1,2-thiazine fused to a 2-azetidinone to for a oxo-5-thia-1-azabicyclo[4.2.0]oct-2-ene-2-carboxylic acid moiety or a derivative thereof.

Organic compounds containing the penicillin core structure, which is structurally characterized by a penam ring bearing two methyl groups at position 2, and an amide group at position 6 [starting from the sulfur atom at position 1].
Lipids formed by joining fatty acids to glycerol by ester bonds.
Organic compounds containing a carboxylic acid substituent attached to a benzene ring.
Compounds containing an imidazopyridine moiety where the pyridine ring bears a ketone group.
Organic compounds containing a carboxamido substituent attached to a benzene ring.
Compounds containing a hippuric acid or a derivative, with a structure characterized the presence of a benzoyl group linked to the N-terminal of a glycine.
Triterpenoids with a structure based on the oleanane skeleton, an 4,4,6a,8a,11,14b-heptamethyl-hexadecahydropicene derivative.
Polyketides having an octahydrotetracene-2-carboxamide skeleton, substituted with many hydroxy and other groups.
Compounds containing 4-(2-Aminoethyl)pyrocatechol [4-(2-aminoethyl)benzene-1,2-diol] or a derivative thereof formed by substitution.
Compounds containing the tryptamine backbone, which is structurally characterized by an indole ring substituted at the 3-position by an ethanamine.

Compounds containing a pheniramine moiety, which is structurally characterized by the presence of a 2-benzylpyridine linked to an dimethyl(propyl)amine to form a dimethyl[3-phenyl-3-(pyridin-2-yl)propyl]amine skeleton.
Compounds containing a phenylmethtylamine moiety, which consists of a phenyl group substituted by an methanamine.
Compounds containing a phenethylamine moiety, which consists of a phenyl group substituted at the second position by an ethan-1-amine.
Compounds containing a phenylpropylamine moiety, which consists of a phenyl group substituted at the third carbon by an propan-1-amine.
Organic compounds containing or derived from 1-phenylpropan-2-amine.
Compounds containing a piperazine ring, which is a saturated aliphatic six-member heterocyclic with two nitrogen atoms at positions 1 and 4, as well as four carbon atoms.
Compounds containing a methoxy group attached to the benzene ring of a phenol moiety.

Organic heterocyclic compounds that contain a nine-membered saturated bicyclic moiety, consisting of two aliphatic saturated rings in a spiro-configuration, each of which contain a nitrogen atom. The bicyclic moiety is made up of two nitrogen and seven carbon atoms.
Compounds belonging to a family of pyridin-2-ylpyrrole based chemicals. The pyrrole is usually fused to a benzene, pyrimidine, or dithiin.
Compounds containing a dioxole ring, which is a five-membered unsaturated ring of two oxygen atoms and three carbon atoms. The dioxoles are divided in meta-dioxoles, and ortho-dioxoles.
Compounds containing a furan ring which bears a nitro group.
Compounds containing a piperidine ring, which is a saturated aliphatic six-member ring with one nitrogen atom and five carbon atoms.
Compounds containing an oxazolidinone moiety, which is an oxazolidine bearing a ketone group.
Compounds containing an oxazolidine ring which bears two ketones.
Carbohydrates made up of 3 to 10 monosaccharide units linked to each other through glycosidic bonds.
Organic polycyclic compounds containing a thioxanthene moiety, which is an aromatic tricycle derived from xanthene by replacing the oxygen atom with a sulfur atom.
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing a xanthene moiety, which consists of two benzene rings joined to each other by a pyran ring.

Vitamin E derivatives containing a saturated trimethyltridecyl chain attached to the carbon C6 atom of a benzopyran ring system. The differ from tocotrienols that contain an unsaturated trimethyltrideca-3,7,11-trien-1-yl chain.
Organic compounds containing a psoralen moiety, which consists of a furan fused to a chromenone to for 7H-furo[3,2-g]chromen-7-one.
Compounds containing a thioxanthene moiety which bears an ketone group.

Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing a xanthene moiety conjugated to a ketone group at carbon 9. Xanthene is a tricyclic compound made up of two benzene rings linearly fused to each other through a pyran ring.
Compounds containing a pyrazole ring which bears a ketone.
Organic aromatic compounds containing a benzene fused to a pyridazine ring.
Compounds containing a phthalazine moiety, which consists of a benzene ring fused to a pyridazine, forming a 2,3-benzodiazine skeleton.
Compounds containing a pyridazine ring which bears a ketone.
Compounds containing a phthalazine bearing a ketone group.
Compounds containing a three ring system containing a pyrrole ring fused on either side to a benzene ring.
Organic compounds containing an indole, which is a bicyclic ring system made up of a six-membered benzene ring fused to a five-membered nitrogen-containing pyrrole ring.
Compounds containing a fundamental skeleton of four pyrrole nuclei united through the alpha-positions by four methine groups to form a macrocyclic structure.

Compounds containing a pyrrolopyridine moiety, which consists of a pyrrole ring fused to a pyridine. Pyrrole is 5-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and one nitrogen atom. Pyridine is a 6-membered ring consisting of five carbon atoms and one nitrogen center.
Eicosanoic acids with an attached hydroxyl group and five CC double bonds.
Compounds containing a saccharide unit which bears a carboxylic acid group.
Polycyclic  compounds containing an indolizine moiety, which is characterized by the presence of a pyrrole ring fused to a pyridine(Pyrrolo[1,2-a]pyridine).
Compounds containing a pyrazolidine ring, which is a five-member saturated aliphatic ring with two nitrogen atoms (at positions 1 and 2) and three carbon atoms.
Compounds containing a pyrrolidine ring, which is a five-membered saturated aliphatic heterocycle with one nitrogen atom and four carbon atoms.
Compounds containing a pyrrolizine moiety, which consists of a pyrrole ring fused to a pyrrolidine ring.
Compounds containing a pyrrolizidine, which is a bicyclic ring system made up of two fused pyrrolidine ring sharing a nitrogen atom.
Compounds containing a quinolizidine moiety, which is a  octahydro-2H-quinolizine derivative.
Compounds containing a quinolizine moiety, which consists of two fused pyridine rings sharing a nitrogen atom.
A phenanthrene derivative where at least one ring CC bond is substituted by hydrogenation.
Cyclic organic compounds containing a thiadiazine ring, which is a six-member unsaturated heterocycle made up of one sulfur atom and two nitrogen atoms.
Compounds containing a thiazole ring which bears a nitro group.
Heterocyclic compounds containing a five-member saturated aliphatic ring with one nitrogen atom, one sulfur atom, three carbon atoms.
Heterocyclic compounds containing a thiazolidinone ring which bears one ketone group.
Heterocyclic compounds containing a thiazolidine ring which bears two ketone groups.
Heterocyclic compounds containing a five-member unsaturated aliphatic ring with one nitrogen atom, one sulfur atom, three carbon atoms.
Organic compounds containing a superoxide oxyanion.
Organic compounds containing a benzene fused to a thiepine ring (a seven-membered ring with six carbon atoms and one sulfur atom).
Compounds containing a dibenzothiepin moiety, which consists of two benzene connected by a thiepine ring.
Organic compounds containing thiolane, a five-member saturated ring containing four carbon atoms and a sulfur atom.
Compounds containing a triazole ring which bears a ketone group.
Compounds containing  a five-member saturated aliphatic ring of two carbon atoms and three nitrogen atoms.
Compounds containing an ellagic acid moiety (4,4',5,5',6,6'-Hexahydroxydiphenic acid 2,6,2',6'-dilactone) or a derivative thereof.
Organic compounds containing a monophosphate linked to an acyl group. They have the general structure  R-CO-P(O)(O)OH, R=H or organyl.

Naturally occurring polyphenols which be categorized into four main classes: hydrolyzable tannin (based on ellagic acid or gallic acid), condensed tannins (made of oligomeric or polymeric proanthocyanidins), complex tannins (made of a catechin bound to a gallotannin or elagitannin), and phlorotannins (oligomers of phloroglucinol).
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing an indolizine fused to a quinonline.

Heterocyclic compounds comprising a planar pentacyclic ring structure, that includes a pyrrolo[3,4-beta]-quinoline moiety (rings A, B and C), conjugated pyridone moiety (ring D) and one chiral center at position 20 within the alpha-hydroxy lactone ring with (S) configuration (the E-ring).
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing a pyran ring fused to an indolizine moiety.
Compounds containing an imidazole ring which bears a nitro group.

Heterocyclic compounds containing a thiophene ring fused to an imidazole ring. Thiophene is 5-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and one sulfur atom. Imidazole is 5-membered ring consisting of three carbon and two nitrogen centers at the 1- and 3-positions.
Organic compounds containing a ureido (tetrahydroimidizalone) ring fused with a tetrahydrothiophene ring.
Aromatic heterocyclic compounds containing a purine moiety, which is formed a pyrimidine-ring ring fused to an imidazole ring.
Compounds containing the purine derivative 1H-purin-6(9H)-one. Purine is a bicyclic aromatic compound made up of a pyrimidine ring fused to an imidazole ring.
Purine derivatives with a ketone group conjugated at carbons 2 and 6 of the purine moiety.
Organic compounds containing 1,2-dioxole, an aliphatic five-member ring with two oxygen atoms in ring positions 1 and 2, and a double bond.
Organic polycyclic compounds containing a thioxanthine moiety, which is an aromatic bicyclic structure derived from xanthine by replacing a carbonyl group with a thiocarbonyl group.
Organic compounds containing an imidazolidine ring, which is a saturated ring (derived from imidazole) with two nitrogen atoms at positions 1 and 3 respectively, and containing only single bonds.

Polycyclic compounds containing an indolizidine, which is a bicyclic heterocycle containing a saturated six-member ring fused to a saturated five-member ring, one of the bridging atoms being nitrogen.
Compounds containing a 1-azabicyclo[2.2.2]octane moiety.

Organic compounds containing a 1,2-diphenylethylene moiety. Stilbenes (C6-C2-C6 ) are derived from the common phenylpropene (C6-C3) skeleton building block. The introduction of one or more hydroxyl groups  to a phenyl ring lead to stilbenoids.
Compounds bearing an ether group with the formula Compounds ROR (R not H).
Heterocyclic compounds based on the 4-[(pteridin-6-ylmethyl)amino]benzoic acid skeleton conjugated with one or more L-glutamate units (or derivatives thereof).
Derivatives of glycerophosphoric acid that contains at least one O-acyl, or O-alkyl, or O-(1-alkenyl) group attached to the glycerol residue.
Lipids  containing backbone of sphingoid bases (e.g. Sphinogsine, sphinganine) usually bound to a fatty acid derivative through N-acylation.

Compounds based on the cyclopenta[a]phenanthrene carbon skeleton, partially or completely hydrogenated; there are usually methyl groups at C-10 and C-13, and often an alkyl group at C-17. By extension, one or more bond scissions, ring expansions and/or ring contractions of the skeleton may have occurred.
Lipids synthesized from the five-carbon-unit precursors isopentenyl diphosphate and dimethylallyl diphosphate.

column2: Monohydroxy bile acids, alcohols and derivatives
column3: Bile acids, alcohols or any of their derivatives bearing a hydroxyl group.

Organic compounds that are synthesized either from the amino acid phenylalanine (phenylpropanoids) or the decarboxylative condensation of malonyl-CoA (polyketides). Phenylpropanoids are aromatic compounds based on the phenylpropane skeleton. Polyketides usually consist of alternating carbonyl and methylene groups (beta-polyketones), biogenetically derived from repeated condensation of acetyl coenzyme A (via malonyl coenzyme A), and usually the compounds derived from them by further condensations.
Aliphatic monocarboxylic acids with a saturated or unsaturated aliphatic tail (with at least 4 Carbon atoms).
Sesquiterpenoids linked to a saccharide moiety through a glycosidic bond.
Compounds an organic acid or a derivative thereof.
Compounds containing a carboxylic acid group with the formula -C(=O)OH or a derivative thereof.
Hydroxy acids with an alkyl chain the contains less than 6 carbon atoms.
Organic compounds containing a bond between a carbon atom and a halogen atom (At, F, Cl, Br, I).
Compounds derived from sulfenic acid, with the general formula R1SR2 ( R1= organyl, R2=any heteroatom).
Compounds derived from sulfinic acid, with the general formula RS(=O)R' ( R not H, R'=any heteroatom).
Compounds containing a sulfonic acid or derivative, with the general structure RS(=O)2X (R=alkyl, aryl; X=any heteroatom).
Compounds containing the carbamic acid functional group, with the general structure RN(R')C(=O)OH or RN(R')C(=O)[O-] where R,R' = H or organyl group.
Organic compounds containing 1,3-dioxole, an aliphatic five-member ring with two oxygen atoms in ring positions 1 and 3 and a double bond.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is chromate, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Organic compounds containing the acridine moiety, a linear tricyclic heterocycle which consists of two benzene rings joined by a pyridine ring.
Organic compounds containing the acryloyl functional group (which has the core fragment but-3-en-2-one).
Organic compounds containing a glycine residue with the N-atom attached to another moiety through an N-ester bond.
Organic compounds containing an alkaline earth metal atom.
Organic compounds containing a nitrogen atom.

Naturally occurring chemical compounds that contain mostly basic nitrogen atoms. This group also includes some related compounds with neutral and even weakly acidic properties. Also some synthetic compounds of similar structure are attributed to alkaloids. In addition to carbon, hydrogen and nitrogen, alkaloids may also contain oxygen, sulfur and more rarely other elements such as chlorine, bromine, and phosphorus.
Ketones containing a carboxylic acid, and an amine group attached to the beta carbon atom, relative to the C=O group.
Benzoic acids (or derivative thereof) containing an amine group attached to the benzene moiety.
Molecules or a portion of a molecule composed of amino-modified sugars.
Organic heterocyclic compounds containing an amino group attached to a pyridine ring.
Organic compounds containing an aminobenzene moiety.
Organic heterocyclic compounds derived from oxoacids RkE(=O)l(OH)m (l not 0) by replacing an OH group by the NHPh group or derivative formed by ring substitution.
Compounds comprising the primary alcohol functional group, with the general structure RCOH (R=alkyl, aryl).
Organic compounds containing a bond between a carbon atom and magnesium atom.
Organic compounds in which the oxygen of an anisole has been replaced by a sulfur.
Compounds containing a nucleobase linked to a ribose or deoxyribose sugar via a beta-glycosidic linkage. The ribose or deoxyribose moiety bears at least a phosphate group in case of nucleotides.
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing the azulene skeleton, which consists of the cyclopentadiene ring fused to a cycloheptadiene ring.
Compounds that contain a pyrimidine ring, which bears a ketone. Pyrimidine is a 6-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and two nitrogen centers at the 1- and 3- ring positions.
Compounds containing a perhydropyrimidine ring substituted at C-2, -4 and -6 by oxo groups.
Organic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to an azepine ring (unsaturated seven-membered heterocycle with one nitrogen atom replacing a carbon atom).
Organic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to an imidazole ring (five member ring containing a nitrogen atom, 4 carbon atoms, and two double bonds).
Organic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to either isomers of diazepine(unsaturated seven-member heterocycle with two nitrogen atoms replacing two carbon atoms).
Organic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to either isomers of dioxole. Dioxole is a five-membered unsaturated ring of two oxygen atoms and three carbon atoms.

Glycerophosphoglycerols  (molecules containing a glycerol moiety attached to the phosphate group linked to a glycerol) in which only one fatty acid is bonded to the 1-glycerol moiety (through an ester linkage).
Long chain aldehydes with a chain of at least 12 carbon atoms.
Hydroxy acids with a 6 to 12 carbon atoms long side chain.
Organic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to an arsole ring (five member ring containing an arsenic atom, 4 carbon atoms, and two double bonds).
Organic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to a furan. Furan is a five-membered aromatic ring with four carbon atoms and one oxygen atom.
Organic compounds containing a benzene fused to an oxazole ring Oxazole is five-membered aromatic ring with a nitrogen and an oxygen atoms at the 1- and 3-position, respectively.
Compounds containing a phenylpiperidine skeleton, which consists of a piperidine bound to a phenyl group.

Compounds containing a pyrazolopyridine skeleton, which consists of a pyrazole fused to a pyridine. Pyrazole is 5-membered ring consisting of three carbon atoms and two adjacent nitrogen centers. Pyridine is a 6-membered ring with four carbon and one nitrogen atoms.

Compounds containing a pyrazolopyrimidine skeleton, which consists of a pyrazole fused to a pyrimidine. Pyrazole is 5-membered ring consisting of three carbon atoms and two adjacent nitrogen centers. Pyrimidine is 6-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and two adjacent nitrogen atoms at the 1- and 3- ring position.
Compounds containing a phenyltetrazole skeleton, which consists of a tetrazole bound to a phenyl group.
Organic compounds containing a saturated seven member heterocycle, with one nitrogen atom.
Organic compounds containing a benzene fused to a thiadiazine ring (a six-member ring with two nitrogen atoms and a sulfur atom).
Organic compounds containing a benzene fused to a thiazine ring (a six-membered ring with four carbon atoms, one nitrogen atom and one sulfur atom).
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing a phenothiazine moiety, which is a linear tricyclic system that consists of a two benzene rings joined by a para-thiazine ring.
Organic compounds containing a benzene fused to a thiazole ring (a five-membered ring with four carbon atoms, one nitrogen atom and one sulfur atom).
Organic compounds containing a benzene fused to a thiepine ring (a five-membered ring with six carbon atoms and one sulfur atom).

Compounds containing a triazole ring fused to a pyrazine ring. Triazole is a five-membered ring consisting of two carbon atoms and three nitrogen atoms. Pyrazine is a 6-membered ring consisting of six carbon atoms and two nitrogen centers at ring positions 1 and 4.

Compounds containing a triazole ring fused to a pyridine ring. Triazole is a five-membered ring consisting of two carbon atoms and three nitrogen atoms. Pyridine is a 6-membered ring consisting of five carbon atoms and one nitrogen center.
Organic compounds containing a benzene fused to a triazole ring (a five-membered ring with two carbon atoms and three nitrogen atoms).
Organic compounds containing a benzene fused to a pyrene(benzo[def]phenanthrene) ring system.
Organic compounds containing a benzene fused to a thiazepine ring (a seven-membered ring with a nitrogen atom and a sulfur atom replacing two carbon atoms).

Compounds comprising the carbamic acid functional group or a derivative thereof. They have the general structure RN(R')C(=O)OH or RN(R')C(=O)R\", where R,R'= H or organyl group, R\"= OH, alkyloxy, acyloxy, or halogen.
Organic compounds containing a benzene fused to an oxazepine ring (a seven-membered ring with four carbon atoms, one oxygen atom, and a nitrogen atom).
Compounds with two benzene rings connected by an azepine ring. Azepine is an unsaturated seven-member heterocycle with one nitrogen atom replacing a carbon atom.
Organic compounds containing an acyl moiety of benzoic acid with the formula (C6H5CO-).
Organic compounds containing an aminoethylpyridine-2,6-dicarboxylic acid derivative.
Organic compounds containing a bond between a carbon atom and an oxygen atom.
Carboxylic ester derivatives of a fatty acid.
Organic compounds containing two phenol groups linked together by a C-C bond.
Organic compounds containing two pyridine rings linked to each other.
Organic compounds containing two phosphonate groups linked together through a carbon atoms.

Organic polycyclic compounds containing an imidazole ring fused to a pyridine ring. Imidazole is 5-membered ring consisting of three carbon atoms, and two nitrogen centers at the 1- and 3-positions. Pyridine is a 6-membered ring consisting of five carbon atoms and one nitrogen center.
Compounds containing a phenylazirine moiety, which consists of an azirine ring attached to a phenyl group.
Compounds containing a phenylbenzimidazole skeleton, which consists of a benzimidazole moiety where its imidazole ring is attached to a phenyl group.
Carboxylic acid amide derivatives of fatty acids, that are formed from a fatty acid and an amine.
Glycerophosphoglycerophosphates in which two fatty acids are bonded to the 1-glycerol moiety through ester linkages.
Fatty acids with a straight aliphatic chain.
Plant secondary metabolites that contain the 2-phenylchromene skeleton. Plant secondary metabolites that contain the 2-phenylchromene skeleton.
Compounds containing an N-acyethanolamine moiety, which is characterized by an acyl group is linked to the nitrogen atom of a piperidine.
Sugar-free counterparts of anthocyanins based on the flavylium ion or 2-phenylchromenylium ion.
Compounds containing a flavan moiety, with a structure characterized by a 2-phenyl-3,4-dihydro-2H-1-benzopyran skeleton.
Fatty acids containing a branched chain.
Fatty acids with a chain that contains at least one CC double bond.
Fatty acids containing a hydroperoxide group attached to the chain.
Fatty acids in which the chain bears a hydroxyl group.
Compounds containing a pyridinylpyrimidine skeleton, which consists of a pyridine linked (not fused) to a pyrimidine by a bond.

Compounds containing a pyrrolopyrazine moiety, which consists of a pyrrole ring fused to a pyrazine. Pyrrole is 5-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and one nitrogen atom. Pyrazine is a 6-membered ring consisting of six carbon atoms and two nitrogen centers at ring positions 1 and 4.

Heterocyclic compounds containing a thiophene ring fused to a pyridine ring. Thiophene is 5-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and one sulfur atom. Pyridine is a 6-membered ring consisting of five carbon atoms and one nitrogen center.
Organic compounds containing a six-member saturated aliphatic ring containing a nitrogen atom, an arsenic atom, and four carbon atoms.
Organic compounds containing exactly two carboxylic acid groups.
Organic compounds containing an amine group, a carboxylic acid group (or a derivative thereof), and a side-chain that is specific to each amino acid.

Compounds containing an amide derived from two or more amino carboxylic acid molecules (the same or different) by formation of a covalent bond from the carbonyl carbon of one to the nitrogen atom of another.
Compounds containing a bond between a carbon atom and an antimony atom.
Compounds containing 1-phenylbutan-1-one moiety.
Diterpenoids with a structure based either on the biflorane or the serrulatane skeleton.
Organic compounds containing a corrin ring, a cobalt atom, an a nucleotide moiety. Cobalamin Derivatives are actually derived from vitamin B12.
Derivatives of the corrin nucleus, which contain four reduced or partly reduced pyrrole rings joined in a macrocycle by three =CH- groups and one direct carbon-carbon bond linking alpha positions.

Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing a coumestan moiety, which consists of a benzoxole fused to a chromen-2-one to form 1-Benzoxolo[3,2-c]chromen-6-one. They are oxidation products of pterocarpan.
Aromatic compounds containing a prop-2-ylbenzene moiety.
Aromatic compounds containing a curcumin moiety, which is composed of two aryl buten-2-one (feruloyl) chromophores joined by a methylene group.
Terpenoids with at least 7 consecutive isoprene units.
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing a furan ring fused to a coumarin moiety.
Heterocyclic compounds containing a saturated four-member ring with three carbon atoms and one sulfur atom.
Heterocyclic compounds containing an unsaturated aliphatic four-member ring with three carbon atoms, one sulfur atom, and one double bond.
Organic compounds comprising the cyanamide functional group, with the general structure R1N=C=NR2.
Compounds having the structure RC#N; thus C-substituted derivatives of hydrocyanic acid, HC#N.
Organic compounds containing the cyanate functional group with the formula [OCN]-.
Compounds comprising the organic carbonic acid or a derivative thereof.
Compounds containing a cyclohexylsulfamic acid moiety.
Compounds containing the nitrosimine functional group, with the general structure O=NN=CR2.
Compounds containing a dihydropyridine moiety, which is a semi-saturated pyridine derivative with two double bonds.
Compounds containing a dioxane ring, which is a six-membered saturated ring of two oxygen atoms and four carbon atoms. The dioxanes are divided in 1,2-dioxanes, 1,3-dioxanes, and 1,4-dioxanes.
Compounds containing a diphenylmethane moiety, which consists of a methane wherein two hydrogen atoms are replaced by two phenyl groups.
Aromatic compounds containing a morpholine ring and a benzene ring linked to each other through a CC or a CN bond.
Organic compounds containing an ergotamine moiety, which is structurally characterized by a benzyl substituent attached to the piperazine ring of the ergopeptine backbone.
Compounds containing the fentanyl moiety or a derivative, which is based on a N-(1-(2-phenylethyl)-4-piperidinyl)-N-phenylpropanamide skeleton.
Carbohydrate derivatives containing a  N-(sulfooxy)ethenimidothioic acid derivative attached to the C1 carbon of glucose moiety.
Compounds comprising the glucuronic acid linked to another substance via a glycosidic bond.
Compounds containing a guanidine moiety, with the general structure (R1R2N)(R3R4N)C=N-R5.
Compounds containing a hydroxamic acid functional group in which a hydroxylamine is inserted into a carboxylic acid. Its general structure is R-CO-NH-OH, with an R as an organic residue.
Heterocyclic compounds containing a saturated three-member ring with two carbon atoms and one sulfur atom.
Compounds comprising a dithietane moiety, which is four-member saturated ring containing two divalent sulfur atoms and two carbon atoms.
Molecules containing an oligomeric moiety of C4-C8 and/or C4-C6 and/or C2-C7 oligo/polymers of flavan-3-ols.
Compounds containing a 1,2,4-trihydroxybenzene moiety.
Quinoline alkaloids containing the dibenzo[de,g]quinoline ring system or a dehydrogenated derivative thereof.
Compounds containing a phloroglucinol (benzene-1,3,5-triol) moiety, which consists of a benzene ring bearing one hydroxyl group at positions 1,3, and 5.
Eicosanoic acids with an attached hydroperoxyl group and three CC double bonds.
Organic compounds comprising the (iso)alloxazine structure (Benzo[g]pteridine-2,4-dione).

Potent cardiotoxic and neurotoxic alkaloids containing a C21-steroid backbone. They have been characterized  from skin extracts of different frog species. The batrachotoxins have a homomorpholine ring at the steroidal CD-ring junction, a 3,9-hemiketal bridge and, in some cases, a 20beta-2,4-dialkylpyrrole-3-carboxylate moiety.
Acylated derivatives of choline. Choline or 2-Hydroxy-N,N,N-trimethylethanaminium is a quaternary ammonium salt with the chemical formula (CH3)3N+(CH2)2OH.
Eicosanoic acids with an attached hydroperoxyl group and four CC double bonds.
Organic compounds in which a carbonyl group is connected by a double bond to an alkylidene group R2C=C=O.
Organic compounds containing a ketone group and a carboxylic acid group.
Polycyclic compounds containing an indolequinone moiety, which consists of an indole bearing two ketones at positions 5 and 6 (or 4 and 7).
Polycyclic compounds with a structure based on an aziridine ring linked to a 7-amino-6-methyl-cyclohexa[b]pyrrolizine-5,8-dione.

Organic compounds containing a morpholine moiety, which consists of a six-member aliphatic saturated ring with the formula C4H9NO, where the oxygen and nitrogen atoms lie at positions 1 and 4, respectively.
Eicosapolyenoic acids (C20 fatty acid with more than one C=C double bonds on the chain).
Ester derivatives of alpha amino acids.
Organic compounds containing the nitrate oxoanion, with the formula NO3-.
Organic compounds containing the nitrite oxoanion, with the formula NO2-.
Compounds containing a 1,2,3-trihydroxybenzene moiety.
Compounds having two beta-haloalkyl groups bound to a nitrogen atom.
Compounds containing a phenylazide moiety, which consists of a linear azide substituent attached to a phenyl group.
Organic compounds containing the phosphorus atom.
Organic compounds containing a phosphine derivative, with the general formula B1P(R2)R3 (R1-R3=alkyl, aryl).
Organic compounds containing phosphoric acid or a derivative thereof.
Organic compounds containing the sulfuric acid or a derivative thereof.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is chromite, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.

Fatty acids containing a ketone group attached to the acyl chain.
Derivatives of diazene(diimide), HN=NH, wherein both hydrogens are substituted by hydrocarbyl groups, e.g. PhN=NPh azobenzene or diphenyldiazene.
Compounds containing the oxime functional group, with the general structure R1(R2)C=NOH.
Compounds containing a dioxetane ring, which is a four-member ring of two oxygen atoms and two carbon atoms. The dioxetanes are divided in 1,2-dioxetanes, and 1,3-dioxetanes.
Compounds containing a pentalene moiety, which consists of two fused cyclopentadiene rings.
Organic compounds containing the peroxide group, with the formula  R1OOR2 (R1,R2=H, alkyl, aryl).
Compounds comprising the boronic acid functional group RB(O)O  (R,R'=alkyl, aryl).
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing a phenazine moiety, which is a linear tricyclic system that consists of a two benzene rings joined by a pyrazine ring.
Compounds containing an anisole where the methane group is linked to an acetic acid or a derivative.
Compounds containing a phenylacetic acid moiety, which consists of a phenyl group substituted at the second position by an acetic acid.
Organic compounds containing phosphonic acid or a derivative thereof.
Organic compounds containing a chlorine atom attached to a dibenzo-p-dioxin moiety.
Lipids containing a methoxy group linked to a fatty acid chain.

Inorganic compounds that contain only non-metal elements.

Organic compounds comprising a five-member nitrogen heterocyclic ring containing at least one other non-carbon atom of either nitrogen, sulfur, or oxygen. The parent compounds are aromatic and have two double bonds; there are successively reduced analogs (azolines and azolidines) with fewer.
Inorganic compounds containing 'other non-metals' and halogen.
Inorganic salt compounds in which the heaviest ionic metal atom is an alkali metal.

Carboxylic acid derivatives containing a carbonyl group in which the carbon atom is linked to a nitrogen atom (substituted or not). The general formula of the carboxylic acid amide is R1C(=O)N(R2)R3 (R1,R2,R3=H, alkyl, aryl).

Compounds having two amino groups bonded to the same carbon,  R2C(NR2)2 where R can by a hydrogen or an alkyl group.
Compounds comprising any derivative of the boronic acid functional group, with the general structure RB(X)Y (R=alkyl, aryl; X,Y= any O, N, Hal residue).
Organic ester derivatives of imidic acid. They have the general structure ROC(CR')=NR\", where R=organyl group, R'-R\"= H or organyl group.
Organic compounds containing at least one chlorine atom attached to either benzene ring of the biphenyl moiety.
Organic compounds containing the isocyanic acid tautomer, HN=C=O, of cyanic acid, HOC#N or its hydrocarbyl derivatives RN=C=O.

Sesquiterpenoids with a structure based on the xanthanolide skeleton consistsing of a cycloheptane ring usually attached to a four-carbon chain (at carbon 1 ) and a methyl group (at carbon 10), and fused to a five-member lactone ring (sharing carbons 7 and 8). The lactone ring can be conjugated with a methyl or methylene group at position 11.
Compounds containing positively charged polyatomic ion of the structure NR4+, R being an alkyl group or an aryl group.
Derivatives of lineolic acid. Lineolic acid is a polyunsaturated omega-6 18 carbon long fatty acid, with two CC double bonds at the 9- and 12-positions.
Compounds containing a sulfonyl group( which as the general structure RS(=O)2R' (R,R' =alkyl, aryl)) attached to two carbon atoms.
Compounds containing a sulfonyl (R-S(=O)2-R') functional group singly bonded to a halogen atom.

Organic compounds containing the sulfonium cation, with the general formula [SR3]+ (R=any atom).
Sulfonamides in which the S-N bond is part of a ring.
Organic compounds containing the functional group with the general structure R-CS-NR'R, where R, R', and R are organic groups.
Biologically active organic compounds containing 12-oxophytodienoic acid, which consists of an oxo-cyclopentene linked to both an octanoic acid chain and pentene chain.
Lipids containing or derived from a jasmonic acid, with a structure characterized by the presence of an alkene chain linked to a 2-(3-oxocyclopentyl)acetic acid moiety.

Organic compounds containing an amide of thiocarboxylic acid, with the general structure R1C(=S)N(R2)R3 (R1-R3=H, alkyl, aryl).
Organic compounds containing the isourea group, with the general structure R1N(R2)C(=NR3)OR4, or its hydrocarbyl derivatives (R1,R2,R3,R4=H, alkyl, aryl).
Organic compounds containing the isothiourea group, with the general structure R1SC(=NR2)N(R3)R4 (R1,R2,R3,R4=H, alkyl, aryl).

Glycerophospholipids in which the O1 and O3 oxygen atoms of the central glycerol moiety are each linked to one 1,2-diacylglycerol chain. Their general formula is OC(COP(O)(=O)OC[C@@H](CO[R1])O[R2])COP(O)(=O)OC[C@@H](CO[R3])O[R4], where R1-R4 are four fatty acyl chains.
Organic compounds containing the isothiocyanate group, an isocyanate analogue with the general formula RN=C=S.
Compounds containing a sulfenic acid functional group, with the general structure RSOH (R not H).
Organic compounds containing the orhtocarboxylic acid functional group, with the RC(X)(X)X (R=H, alkyl, aryl; X=OH, alkoxy, aryloxy, substituted amino, etc.).
Carboxylic acid derivatives containing a carbon atom form three single bonds, each with one oxygen atom.
Carboxylic acid derivatives in which the carbon atom from the carbonyl group is attached to an alkyl or an aryl moiety through an oxygen atom (forming an ester group).
Carboxylic acid derivatives a carbonyl group in which the carbon is directly linked to an azide group (-N=N+=N-).
Carboxylic acid derivatives two carbonyl groups where the carbon atoms are both linked to the same oxygen atom.
Cyclic esters of caproic acid. Caproic acid is the carboxylic acid derived from hexane with the general formula C5H11COOH.
Compounds containing a phenylthiazole moiety, which consists of an thiazole ring attached to a phenyl group.
Organic compounds containing a four-member lactone (a cyclic ester).
Cyclic organic compounds containing an oxan-2- one moiety.

Compounds containing a gamma butyrolactone moiety, which consists of an aliphatic five-member ring with four carbon atoms, one oxygen atom, and bears a ketone group on the carbon adjacent to the oxygen atom.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest oxoanion is plumbite, and in which the heaviest atom not in an oxoanion is a metalloid.
Organic compounds containing fluorophosphonic acid or a derivative thereof.
Compounds containing a hydroxybenzoic acid (or a derivative), which is a benzene ring bearing a carboxyl and a hydroxyl groups.
Compounds containing a flavin (7,8-dimethyl-benzo[g]pteridine-2,4-dione) moiety, with a structure characterized by an isoalloaxzine tricyclic ring.
Compounds containing a [2-(trimethylazaniumyl)ethoxy]phosphonic acid or derivative.
Compounds containing a 3,4,5-trihydroxybenzoic acid moiety.
Compounds containing an acetic acid (or a derivative) linked to the C3 carbon atom of an indole.
Compounds containing a quinoline moiety, which consists of a benzene ring fused to a pyrimidine ring to form benzo[b]azabenzene.
Compounds containing glycerophosphate moiety attached to a 1-alkenyl group.
Organic compounds containing a carboxamide group linked to an imidazole ring.
Glycerolipids containing a diacylglycerol, with a cytidine diphosphate attached to the oxygen O1 or O2 of the glycerol part.
Compounds containing a phenylacetaldehyde moiety, which consists of a phenyl group substituted at the second position by an acetalydehyde.
Compounds containing or derived from a neuraminic acid moiety (5-amino-3,5-dideoxy-D-glycero-D-galacto-non-2-ulosonic acid), which is a 9-carbon monosaccharide.
Organic compounds containing the bromate oxoanion, with the formula BrO3-.
Organic compounds containing the chlorate oxoanion, with the formula  ClO3-.
Organic compounds containing the chlorite oxoanion, with the formula  ClO2-.
Organic compounds containing an amino group attached to a pyrimidine ring. Pyrimidine is a 6-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and two nitrogen centers at the 1- and 3- ring positions.

Glycerolipids with a cytidine diphosphate attached to the oxygen O1 or O2 of the glycerol part. As is the case with diacylglycerols, phosphatidylserines can have many different combinations of fatty acids of varying lengths and saturation attached to the C-1 and C-2 atoms.
Glycerolipids containing a monoacylglycerol, with a cytidine diphosphate attached to the oxygen O1 or O2 of the glycerol part.
Organonitrogen compounds with the general formula RN(R')N=S=O (R,R' = H or organyl).
Compounds containing a phosphate linked to the second carbon of an ethanolamine.
Organic compounds containing the aldimine functional group.
Pyridine nucleotides, in which the pyridine base is nicotinamide or a derivative thereof.
Compounds containing a sulfinic acid functional group, with the general structure RS(=O)OH (R = organyl, not H).
Inorganic compounds containing non-metal as well as metal atoms but not belonging to afore mentioned classes.
Compounds containing a thiodiacetic acid group (or esters/salts thereof) which is made up of two 2-sulfanylacetic (OC(=O)CS) acid moieties sharing their sulfur atom.
Aromatic compounds containing a methoxyphenol moiety.
Aromatic compounds containing a meta-cresol moiety, which consists of a benzene ring bearing a methyl group and a hydroxyl group at ring positions 1 and 3, respectively.
Organic compounds containing an ortho-cresol moiety, which consists of a benzene bearing one hydroxyl group at ring positions 1 and 2, respectively.
Compounds containing a para cresol moiety, which consists of a benzene ring bearing one hydroxyl group at ring positions 1 and 4.
Compounds containing a phenylpyruvic acid moiety, which consists of a phenyl group substituted at the second position by an pyruvic acid.
Organic compounds formed by eight consecutive isoprene fragments. Carotenoids are a subgroup of tetraterpenes, and are subdivided in two categories: Carotenes and Xanthophylls.
Organic compounds containing the chromate oxoanion, with the formula   [CrO4]2-.
Compounds containing having two beta-haloalkyl groups bound to a sulfur atom.
Organic compounds containing an aldehyde substituted with a keto group on the adjacent carbon.
Quaternary ammonium compounds containing a trimethyl-(10-trimethylammoniodecyl)ammonium moiety.
Organic compounds containing a N,N,N,N',N',N'-hexamethylhexane-1,6-diaminium moiety.
Prenol lipids containing a lactone ring.

Terpene lactones structurally characterized by the presence of an indeno[1,2-b]furan and a 2,5-dihydrofuran-2-one linked together to form a 3-methyl-5-{8-methyl-2-oxo-indeno[1,2-b]furan-3-ylidene]methoxy}-2,5-dihydrofuran-2-one skeleton.
Compounds containing a thiamine moiety, which is structurally characterized by a 3-[(4-Amino-2-methyl-pyrimidin-5-yl)methyl]-4-methyl-thiazol-5-yl backbone.
Organic compounds containing two hydroxyl groups attached to a benzene ring.
Thiamine derivatives in which the hydroxyl group of the ethanol moiety is substituted by a phosphate group.
Glycerophosphates in which the glycerol moiety is bonded to two aliphatic (saturated or unsaturated) chains through ether linkages.
Glycerophosphocholines in which the glycerol moiety is bonded to two aliphatic (saturated or unsaturated) chains through ether linkages.
Compounds containing a carboxylic acid chain (of at least 2 carbon atoms) linked to an indole ring.
Polycyclic compounds containing a pyran ring fused to a quinoline moiety.  Quinoline or benzo[b]pyridine is a bicyclic compound that consists of benzene fused to a pyridine.
Organic compounds containing an aliphatic ring substituted with at least one hydroxyl group.
Purine nucleotides bound to a saccharide derivative through the terminal phosphate group.
Compounds containing a polyisoprene chain attached to a quinone at the second ring position.
Compounds containing an steroid backbone, with at least one hydrogen substituted by a hydroxyl group.
Pyrimidine nucleotides bound to a saccharide derivative through the terminal phosphate group.
Compounds containing a (deoxy)ribose phosphate with the ribose unit N-linked to a pyridine ring.

Glycerophosphoglycerols that carry exactly one acyl chain attached to the glycerol moiety through an ester linkage at the O1-position,  and one acyl chain attached through an ether linkage at the O2-position.
Glycerol-3-phosphates in which the glycerol moiety is bonded to two aliphatic chains through ester linkages.
Pyridine nucleotides, in which the pyridine base is nicotinic acid or a derivative thereof.
acyclic branched or unbranched hydrocarbons having a carbon-carbon triple bond and the general formula CnH2n-2.
Organic compounds containing phosphonic acid.
Organic compounds containing the thiophosphoric acid functional group or a derivative thereof, with the general structure RP(R')(R'')=S, where R,R',R'' = O,N, halogen residue.

A group of cyclic polyether compounds produced naturally by a species of dinoflagellate known as Karenia brevis. They contain a Pentaoxapentacycloheptacos- 23-en-7-one derivative (type a brevetoxin) or a pentaoxapentacyclotetracosa- 8,23-dien-7-one derivative (type b brevetoxin).
Organic compounds containing the isomer HN+#C- of hydrocyanic acid, HC#N, or its hydrocarbyl derivatives RNC (RN+#C-).
Organic compounds containing the chromate oxoanion, with the formula Cr(O2)−.
Organic compounds comprising the hydroperoxide functional group, with the general formula [O-O]2-.
Organic compounds containing the phosphine oxide group, with the general formula R3P=O or R3P+O-.
Organic compounds containing three hydroxyl groups attached to a benzene ring.
Prenol lipids containing a phosphate group linked to an isoprene (2-methylbuta-1,3-diene) unit.
Organic compounds containing 1,2-dioxane, an aliphatic six-member ring with two oxygen atoms in ring positions 1 and 2.
Organic compounds containing 1,4-dioxane, an aliphatic six-member ring with two oxygen atoms in ring positions 1 and 4.
Organic compounds containing 1,3-dioxane, an aliphatic six-member ring with two oxygen atoms in ring positions 1 and 3.
Organic compounds containing 1,2-dioxolane, an aliphatic five-member ring with two oxygen atoms in ring positions 1 and 2.
Organic compounds containing 1,3-dioxolane, an aliphatic five-member ring with two oxygen atoms in ring positions 1 and 3.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest oxoanion is ferrate, and in which the heaviest atom not in an oxoanion is a transition metal.
Compounds containing hippuric acid, which consists of a of a benzoyl group linked to the N-terminal of a glycine.
Compounds containing a pyrimidine ring which bears a carboxylic acid group (or a derivative thereof).
Glycerophosphates where the glycerol is esterified with one fatty acid linked to the phosphate group at position O-3.
Compounds containing a pyrimidine ring which bears a carboxamide.
Compounds containing a pyridine ring bearing a carboxylic acid group or a derivative thereof.
Compounds containing a pyrrolizidine moiety which bears a ketone. Pyrrolizidine is a bicyclic ring system made up of two fused pyrrolidine ring sharing a nitrogen atom.
Glycerophosphoinositol phosphates where the glycerol is esterified with two fatty acids.
Compounds containing a quinolizidine moiety which bears a ketone group.
Compounds containing a pyridine ring bearing a carboxamide.
Compounds containing a triazolidine ring which bears a ketone group.
Organic compounds containing a 3-oxo acylated coenzyme A derivative.
Nucleotides containing a flavin moiety. Flavin is a compound that contains the tricyclic isoalloxazine ring system, which bears 2 oxo groups at the 2- and 4-positions.
Glycerophosphoinositol monophosphates where the glycerol is esterified with one fatty acid.
Organic compounds containing a 1,2-hydroxy ketone attached to two phenyl groups.
Polycyclic compounds containing an indolizine moiety bearing a ketone.
Inorganic compounds containing the sulfuryl chloride functional group, with the general structure XS(R)(=O)=O (X=Br,Cl,F,I; R=hetero atom).
Aliphatic alcohols consisting of a chain of a least six carbon atoms.
Organic compounds containing 1,2-diazepine, a seven-member heterocyclic ring with two nitrogen atoms in positions 1 and 2.
Organic compounds containing 1,4-diazepine, a seven-member heterocyclic ring with two nitrogen atoms in positions 1 and 4.
Organic compounds containing 1,3-diazepine, a seven-member heterocyclic ring with two nitrogen atoms in positions 1 and 3.
Organic compounds containing an aromatic seven-membered ring containing a nitrogen and an oxygen atom, a positions 1 and 2, respectively.
Organic compounds containing an aromatic seven-membered wring containing a nitrogen and an oxygen atom, a positions 1 and 4, respectively.
Organic compounds containing an aromatic seven-membered wring containing a nitrogen and an oxygen atom, a positions 1 and 3, respectively.
Organic compounds containing 1,3-oxazine, a six-member ring with a nitrogen and an oxygen atoms in ring positions 1 and 3 respectively, as well as two double bonds.
Organic compounds containing 1,4-oxazine, a six-member ring with a nitrogen and an oxygen atoms in ring positions 1 and 4 respectively, as well as two double bonds.
Organic compounds containing 1,2-oxazine, a six-member ring with a nitrogen and an oxygen atoms in ring positions 1 and 2 respectively, as well as two double bonds.
Glycerophosphoinositols where the glycerol is esterified with two fatty acids.
Organic compounds containing a benzene ring with a formyl substituent.
Organic compounds containing a five-member heterocyclic compound with five nitrogen atoms, and two nitrogen atoms at positions 1 and 2 (Pyridazines), 1 and 3 (Pyrimidines), or 1 and 4 (Pyrazines).
Organic compounds containing 1,3-thiazine, a six-member ring with a nitrogen and a sulfur atoms in ring positions 1 and 3 respectively, as well as two double bonds.
Organic compounds containing 1,2-thiazine, a six-member ring with a nitrogen and a sulfur atoms in ring positions 1 and 2 respectively, as well as two double bonds.
Organic compounds containing 1,4-thiazine, a six-member ring with a nitrogen and a sulfur atoms in ring positions 1 and 4 respectively, as well as two double bonds.
Ester derivatives of benzoic acid.
Triterpenoids that do not contain a cycle.
Aromatic compounds containing meta thiazepine moiety, which is an unsaturated seven-member heterocyclic compound, with five carbon atoms, and two sulfur atoms at position 1 and 3.
Compounds containing a thiazepine ring, in which the sulfur and nitrogen atoms are at positions 1 and 2 respectively.

Compounds containing a para thiazepine moiety, which consists of an unsaturated seven-member ring with one nitrogen atom and one sulfur at positions 1 and 4, respectively, as well as two CC double bonds.
Glycerophosphoinositols  (molecules containing an inositol moiety attached to the phosphate group linked to a glycerol) where the glycerol is esterified with one fatty acid.
Monosaccharides with a single carbohydrate unit, which contains three carbon atoms.
Diterpenoids (compounds made of four consecutive isoprene units) that do not contain a cycle.

Glycerophosphoglycerols in which two fatty acids are bonded to the 1-glycerol moiety through ester linkages. As is the case with diacylglycerols, phosphatidylglycerols can have many different combinations of fatty acids of varying lengths and saturation attached to the C-1 and C-2 positions.
Organic compounds containing a carboxylic acid substituted with a hydroxyl group on the adjacent carbon.
Inorganic compounds containing only metal atoms of at least two different types, where the heaviest atom is an alkali metal.
Organic compounds containing a flavylium ion or 2-phenylchromenylium based skeleton bound to a sugar.
Compounds containing a flavan-3-one moiety, with a structure characterized by a 2-phenyl-3,4-dihydro-2H-1-benzopyran bearing a hydroxyl group and a ketone at the carbon C2 and C3, respectively.
Compounds containing the enone functional group, with the structure RC(=O)CR'.
Organic compounds comprising the hydroxide functional group, with the general formula OH-.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest oxoanion is chromite, and in which the heaviest atom not in an oxoanion is a alkaline earth metal.
Organic compounds containing a saccharide unit that bears both an amine group and a carboxylic acid group.

Glycerophosphoserines in which two fatty acids are bonded to the glycerol moiety through ester linkages. As is the case with diacylglycerols, phosphatidylserines can have many different combinations of fatty acids of varying lengths and saturation attached to the C-1 and C-2 positions.
Organic compounds containing a functional group with the general structure OC(=S)NR2 or SC(=O)NR2.
Compounds comprising the boronic acid ester functional group RN(X)OR' (R,R'=alkyl, aryl; X= any O, N, Hal residue).
Organic compounds containing a metalloid atom.
Organic compounds containing a transition metal atom.
Organic compounds containing an alkali metal atom.
Organic compounds containing the ynone functional group, an alpha,beta unsaturated ketone group with the general structure  RC#C-C(=O)R' (R'  not H).

Pyridoindoles with a structure that contains an indole moiety bearing a ketone. Indole is a bicyclic  compound consisting of a six-membered benzene ring fused to a five-membered nitrogen-containing pyrrole ring.
Organic compounds containing the cyanohydrin functional group, -C(OH)CN.
Organic compounds containing an aldehyde substituted with a keto group on the second carbon atom.
Glycerophosphoserines  (molecules containing a serine moiety attached to the phosphate group linked to a glycerol) with one fatty acid bonded to the glycerol moiety through an ester linkage.
Organic compounds containing a chlorine atom attached to a dibenzofuran moiety.
Organic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to a 1,4-dioxin ring.
N-acyl hexosamines in which the hexose is substituted by a phosphate group at position 1.
Compounds containing a dibenzo-p-dioxin moiety, which consists of two benzene connected by a para-dioxin ring.
Organic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to a 1,2-dioxin ring.
Organic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to a 1,3-dioxin ring.
Compounds containing a dioxin ring, which is a six-membered unsaturated ring of two oxygen atoms and four carbon atoms.
Compounds containing a dioxin ring, in which the two oxygen atoms are at positions 1 and 2 respectively.
Compounds containing a para dioxin moiety, which consists of an unsaturated six-member ring with two oxygen atoms at positions 1 and 4, as well as two CC double bonds.
Tautomeric forms of sultams, having a sulfur-nitrogen double bond as part of a ring.
Sphingolipids in which the sphingosine base is linked to a glucuronic acid moiety.
Neoflavonoids with a structure based on the 4-phenylcoumarin skeleton.

Compounds containing the benzo[a]heptalene based colchicin moiety or a derivative thereof. Colchicine is a tricyclic compound consisting of a benzene ring angularly fused to a tetrahydroheptalene  that carries a N-acetamide group.
Compounds containing an cinnamic acid (or a derivative thereof) where the benzene ring is hydroxylated.

Plant products of low molecular weight formed primarily from oxidative coupling of two p-propylphenol moieties. They can also be described as micromolecules with two phenylpropanoid units coupled together. They can be attached in various manners, like C5-C5', C8-C8'. Most known natural lignans are oxidized at C9 and C9´ and, based upon the way in which oxygen is incorporated into the skeleton and on the cyclization patterns, a wide range of lignans of very different structural types can be formed.
Glycerophosphoetahnolamines in which two fatty acids are bonded to the glycerol moiety through ester linkages.
Ceramides with phosphoethanolamine as substituent. Phosphoethanolamine is an organophosphorus compound with the general structure NCCOP(O)(O)=O.
Glycerophosphoserines that contain exactly two fatty acyl chains attached to the glycerol moiety, one through an ester and the other through an ether linkage.
Organic compounds containing a benzene fused to an oxazine ring (a six-membered aliphatic ring with four carbon atoms, one oxygen atom, and one nitrogen atom).

Glycerophosphates that carry exactly one acyl chain attached to the glycerol moiety through an ester linkage at the O2-position,  and one 1Z-alkenyl chain attached through an ether linkage at the O1-position.
Inorganic non-metallic compounds containing a bisulfite as its largest oxoanion.
Ceramides with phosphoinositol as substituent.
Organic compounds containing the nitrosamine functional group, with the structure R2NN=O.

Monoterpenoids with a structure based on the o-, m-, or p-menthane backbone. P-menthane consists of the cyclohexane ring with a methyl group and a (2-methyl)-propyl group at the 1 and 4 ring position, respectively. The o- and m- menthanes are much rarer, and presumably arise by alkyl migration of p-menthanes.
Organic compounds containing an imidazolinone moiety, which is an imidazoline ring bearing a ketone.
Steroids containing ergosta-5,7,22-trien-3beta-ol or a  derivative thereof, which is based on the 3beta-hydroxylated ergostane skeleton.

Glycerophosphates  in which the O-1 atom of the glycerol is bonded to a fatty acid (saturated or unsaturated) through an ether linkage, and the O-2 atom is bonded to another fatty acid through an ester linkage.

Glycerophosphoetahnolamines  (molecules containing an ethanolamine moiety attached to the phosphate group linked to a glycerol) with one  fatty acid chain bonded to the glycerol moiety through an ester linkage.
Compounds containing glycerophosphate moiety attached to an fatty acyl chain through an ether bond.

Glycerophosphoserines that carry exactly one acyl chain attached to the glycerol moiety through an ester linkage at the O2-position,  and one 1Z-alkenyl chain attached through an ether linkage at the O1-position.
Glycerophosphocholines in which the two free -OH are attached to one fatty acid each through an ester linkage.

Glycerophosphoethanolamines that carry exactly one acyl chain attached to the glycerol moiety through an ester linkage at the O1-position,  and one alkyl chain attached through an ether linkage at the O2-position.

Carotenoids containing an oxygenated carotene backbone. Carotenes are characterized by the presence of two end-groups (mostly cyclohexene rings, but also cyclopentene rings or acyclic groups) linked by a long branched alkyl chain. Carotenes belonging form a subgroup of the carotenoids family. Xanthophylls arise by oxygenation of the carotene backbone.

A type of unsaturated hydrocarbons containing eight consecutive isoprene units. They are characterized by the presence of two end-groups (mostly cyclohexene rings, but also cyclopentene rings or acyclic groups) linked by a long branched alkyl chain. Carotenes belonging form a subgroup of the carotenoids family.
Organic compounds containing the imidazole ring linked to a ribose phosphate through a 1-2 bond.
