Glycerophosphocholines (molecules containing a choline moiety attached to the phosphate group linked to a glycerol) in which the glycerol is esterified with  one fatty acid each through an ester linkage.
Compounds containing glycerophosphocholine moiety attached to an fatty acyl chain through an ether bond.
Keto acids with a 6 to 12  carbon atoms long side chain.
Keto acids with an alkyl chain the contains less than 6 carbon atoms.
Organic compounds containing the imidazolecarboxamide linked to a ribose phosphate through a 1-2 bond.
Lipid molecules containing a sphingosine in which the amine group is linked to a fatty acid.

Glycosphingolipids in which the ceramide skeleton  is bound to an oligosaccharide (usually 3 to 5 units) moiety made up of a glucose (as primary unit bound to the ceramide moiety) and galactose (Gal), N-acetylglucosamine (GlcNAc), N-acetylgalactosamine (GalNAc) or mannose (Man) as the other monosaccharides.
Organic compounds containing the imidazole ring linked to a ribose ring through a 1-2 bond.
Compounds containing an ester derivative of glycidol (2,3-Epoxy-1-propanol).
Hydroxyeicosapolyenoic acids which do not belong to the Hydroxyeicosapentaenoic acids, the Hydroxyeicosatetraenoic acids, or the Hydroxyeicosatrienoic acids.
Fatty acid derivatives obtained by insertion of a sulfur atom at specific positions in the chain.
Lipids containing either the sphingosine-phosphocholine, or the sphinganine-phosphocholine core structure.
Fatty acids containing linked to a sulfate group linked to its tail.
Lipids structurally characterized by the presence of a glycerol moiety bonded to two aliphatic chains through ester linkages, and to a pyrophosphate group.
Compounds containing an n-acyl-ceramide phosphate skeleton.
Compounds containing a ceramide linked to a simple glycosyl moiety.
Neutral glycosphingolipids in which the root sequence of the oligosaccharide moiety is GalNAcb1-3Gala1-4Galb1-4Glc.
Neutral glycosphingolipids in which the root sequence is GalNAcb1-4GlcNAcb1-3Manb1-4Glc.
Neutral glycosphingolipids in which the root sequence of the oligosaccharide moiety is Galb1-3GlcNAcb1-3Galb1-4Glc.

Neutral glycosphingolipids in which the root sequence of the oligosaccharide moiety is Galb1-4GlcNAcb1-3Galb1-4Glc. The differ from lacto series because of their 1-4 (instead of 1-3) bond between Galb and GlcNacb.

Neutral glycosphingolipids in which the root sequence of the oligosaccharide moiety is GalNAcb1-3Gala1-3Galb1-4Glcb. The differ from lacto series because of their 1-3 (instead of 1-4) bond between Gala and Glacb.

Organic compounds containing a glycoside of indolium-2-carboxylic acid attached, with the nitrogen ring of the indolium ring attached to an ethylpyridine-2,6-dicarboxylic acid derivative. Betacyanins are red nitrogenous pigments found in certain plants, such as beetroots.
Organic compounds belonging to the class of Betaxanthins or Betacyanins. This class also contains derivatives of betalamic acid, which is the precursor of betalains.
Neutral glycosphingolipids in which the root sequence of the oligosaccharide moiety is GlcNAcb1-2Mana1-3Manb1-4Glc.
Organic compounds containing a benzene fused to an oxazine ring (a six-member aliphatic ring with four carbon atoms, one oxygen atom, and one nitrogen atom) bearing a ketone group.

Organic derivatives of thiophosphonic acid, thiophosphoric acid, dithiophosphoric acid, or phosphorotrithioic acid, or derivatives thereof. Thiophosphonic acid, dithiophosphoric acid, thiophosphoric acid, and phosphorotrithioic acid are thiophosphorus compounds with the formula OP(O)(=S), OP(S)(=S)O, OP(O)(=S)O, and OP(=S)(S)S, respectively.

Lipid molecules composed of a glycosphingolipid (ceramide and saccharide) with one or more sialic acids linked on the sugar chain. They are usually oligoglycosylceramides derived from lactosylceramide and containing a sialic acid residue such as N-acetylneuraminic acid.
An hydrogen sulfate esters of glycosphingolipids.
Compounds containing an amino acid esterified with a carbohydrate.
Inorganic compounds containing a non-metal atom linked to a metallic oxoanionic moiety.

Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing triazole ring fused to a pyrimidine ring. Triazole is a five-membered ring consisting of two carbon atoms and three nitrogen atoms. Pyrimidine is a 6-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and two nitrogen centers at the 1- and 3- ring positions.
Organic compounds containing the hypobromite oxoanion, with the formula BrO-.
Organic compounds containing an alcohol or acid derivative of cholic acid.

Heterocyclic compounds containing a thiophene ring fused to an imidazolidine ring. Thiophene is 5-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and one sulfur atom. Imidazolidine is 5-membered saturated ring of three carbon atoms, and two nitrogen centers at the 1- and 3-positions.
Sterol lipids containing a glucuronide moiety linked to the steroid skeleton.
Organic compounds containing a furoic acid moiety, with a structure characterized by a furan ring bearing a carboxylic acid group at the C2 or C3 carbon atom.
Inorganic compounds containing only metal atoms of at least two different types, where the heaviest atom is a lanthanide.
Inorganic compounds containing only metal atoms of at least two different types, where the heaviest atom is lanthanide.
Inorganic compounds containing only metal atoms of at least two different types, where the heaviest atom is a actinide metal.
Compounds containing only metal atoms of at least two different types, where the heaviest atom is a metalloid.
Inorganic compounds containing only metal atoms of at least two different types, where the heaviest atom is a transition metal.
Inorganic compounds containing only metal atoms of at least two different types, where the heaviest atom is a post-transition metal.
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing four pyrrole rings joined by one-carbon units linking position 2 of one pyrrole ring to position 5 of the next.
Organic compounds containing the 5-thia-1-azabicyclo[4.2.0]octan-8-one nucleus.
Organic heterocyclic compounds containing a penem moiety, which is a 2,3-didehydropenam derivative.
Compounds containing a the cephalosporin (oxo-5-thia-1-azabicyclo[4.2.0]oct-2-ene-2-carboxylic acid) nucleus, with an alkyloxy group attached to the C6 carbon atom.
Glycerolipids structurally characterized by the presence of one or more sugar residues attached to the glycerol moiety of a glycerophosphate via a glycosidic linkage.
Compounds containing a secosteroid backbone, usually secoergostane or secocholestane.
Organic compounds similar to the pyrethrins. Some pyrethroids containing a chrysanthemic acid esterified with a cyclopentenone (pyrethrins), or with a phenoxybenzyl group.
Lipids containing a mannosylerylthritol skeleton, which is 1-O-b-mannopyranosyl-meso-erythritol.
Organic compounds containing a 3-hydroxyalkanoic acid linked to another 3-hydroxyalkanoic acid through the hydroxyl group at the 3-position.
Organic compounds containing a quinoline moiety with a hydroxyl group attached to the C4 atom, and an alkyl chain attached to the C2 atom.
Organic compounds containing or derived from anatoxin, homoanatoxin or other analogues. Anatoxins constitute a class of potent neurotoxic alkaloids.
Steroids with a structure based on the estrane skeleton.
3-hydroxylated C19 steroid hormones. They are known to favor the development of masculine characteristics. They also show profound effects on scalp and body hair in humans.
Steroids with a structure based on a hydroxylated prostane moiety.
Compounds containing a 3-hydroxylated cholestane core.
Inorganic compounds containing a metallic oxoanion to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is aluminate, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is antimonate, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is antimonite, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is arsenate, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is arsenite, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is borate, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is ferrate, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is manganate, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is molybdate, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is plumbate, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is plumbite, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is silicate, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is stannate, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is stannite, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is tellurate, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is tellurite, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is tetrahydroxyborate, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is tungstate, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest metallic oxoanion is orthovanadate, to which either no atom or a non metal atom is bonded.
Compounds containing an esterified cholestane moiety.
Purine nucleotides where one ribose group of the hydroxyl moiety and one phosphate group form a ring.
Pyrimidine nucleotides where one ribose group of the hydroxyl moiety and one phosphate group form a ring.
Compounds containing an epibatidine moiety, with a structure characterized by a 2-chloropyridine moiety connected to an 7-azabicyclo[2.2.1]heptane in exo position.
Purine nucleotides in which the oxygen atoms linked to the C2 and C3 carbon atoms of the ribose moiety are both bonded the same phosphorus atom of the phosphate group.
Pyrimidine nucleotides in which the oxygen atoms linked to the C2 and C3 carbon atoms of the ribose moiety are both bonded the same phosphorus atom of the phosphate group.
Monosaccharides with a sugar unit made up of 4 atoms.
Monosaccharides in which the carbohydrate moiety contains five carbon atoms.
Monosaccharides in which the sugar unit is a is a six-carbon containing moeity.
Monosaccharides in which the sugar unit is a seven-carbon containing moeity.
Monosaccharide compounds in which the sugar moiety is an octose (8 carbon atoms).
Monosaccharide compounds in which the sugar moiety is an octose (9 carbon atoms).
Purine nucleotides in which the oxygen atoms linked to the C3 and C5 carbon atoms of the ribose moiety are both bonded the same phosphorus atom of the phosphate group.
Pyrimidine nucleotides in which the oxygen atoms linked to the C3 and C5 carbon atoms of the ribose moiety are both bonded the same phosphorus atom of the phosphate group.
Glycerophosphates in which the glycerol is esterified ta two positions with to fatty acids.
Purines that carry a C=O group at position 6. Purine is a bicyclic aromatic compound made up of a pyrimidine ring fused to an imidazole ring.
Nucleotides with a purine base attached to the ribosyl moiety.
Organic compounds containing a functional group with the general structure HOC(=S)N(R1)R2 (R=halogen; R1,R2=H, alkyl, aryl).
Organic compounds comprising the oxoazanium cation, with the formula N+=O.
Nucleotides containing a pyrimidine base.
Lignans that contain a lactone moiety. They include 1-aryltetralin lactones, dibenzylbutyrolactone lignans, and podophyllotoxins, among others.
Aromatic polycyclic compounds containing a carbohydrate component glycosidically linked to a lignan moiety. They include 1-aryltetralin lactones.
Glycerolipids that do not belong to either the class Alk(en)yl Diacylglycerols, Diacylglycerols, Glycosylglycerols, Monoacylglycerols, Other Glycerolipids or Triacylglycerols.
Quinolines in which the quinoline ring system is substituted by one sulfonamide group at the 3-position.
Compounds containing a chemical bond between a carbon atom and an astatin atom.
Compounds containing a chemical bond between a carbon atom and a bromine atom.
Compounds containing a chemical bond between a carbon atom and a chlorine atom.
Compounds containing a chemical bond between a carbon atom and a fluorine atom.
Compounds containing a chemical bond between a carbon atom and an iodine atom.
Organic compounds containing the functional group -CO-As.
Organic compounds containing the nitrosonium cation, with the general formula NO+.
Compounds comprising the carbonic acid functional group.
Lipids containing a trehalose molecule linked to at least one fatty acid through an ester bond.
Organic compounds containing a post-transition metal atom.
Compounds containing bond between a carbon atom and a tin atom.
Hydroperoxyeicosapolyenoic acids which do not belong to the hydroperoxyeicosapentaenoic acids, the hydroperoxyeicosatetraenoic acids, or the hydroperoxyeicosatrienoic acids.
Organic compounds containing the hypochlorite oxoanion, with the formula ClO-.
Cyclic aromatic compounds containing a diphenylacetonitrile moiety, which consists of a diphenylmethane linked to and acetonitrile to form 2,2-diphenylacetonitrile.
Fatty acids containing a 5-alkylfuran-2-alkanoic acid.
Compounds containing bond between a carbon atom and an aluminum atom.
Organic compounds containing a benzene bearing a nitrile substituent.

Fatty acids structurally characterized by the presence of a furanoid ring substituted at the positions 1, 2, 3, and 4 by a short fatty acid chain, a carboxylic acid group, a methyl group, and an alkyl chain, respectively.
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing a cyclopenten-2-one ring fused to the coumarin moiety of the difurocoumarin skeleton.
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing a delta-valerolactone ring fused to the coumarin moiety of the difurocoumarin skeleton.
Lipids structurally characterized by the presence of a quinone or hydroquinone moiety.
Prenols with more than 4 consecutive isoprene units.
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing difurocoumarin moiety consisting of a system of two fused furan rings, which is linked to the benzene ring of a coumarin.
Fatty acids containing an oxirane ring as part of the aliphatic chain.
Diterpenoids containing a lactone moiety.
Compounds containing more than ten saccharide units.

Compounds containing one carbohydrate unit not glycosidically linked to another such unit, and no set of two or more glycosidically linked carbohydrate units. Monosaccharides have the general formula CnH2nOn.
Monosaccharides comprising a phosphated group linked to the carbohydrate unit.
Compounds containing two carbohydrate moieties linked to each to each other through a glycosidic bond, no set of three or more glycosidically linked carbohydrate units.
Sesquiterpenoids containing a lactone ring.
Nucleotides consisting of a purine base linked to a ribose to which at least one phosphate group is attached.
Coenzyme Q derivatives containing a 5, 6-dimethoxy-3-methyl(1,4-benzoquinone) moiety to which an isoprenyl group is attached at ring position 2(or 6).
A group of fat-soluble compounds containing or derived either from a tocopherol or a tocotrienol skeleton.
Quinone lipids containing a methylated naphthoquinone ring structure, and vary in the aliphatic side chain attached at the 3-position.
Carboxylic acids (or derivative thereof) containing a halogen atom bonded to the alpha carbon atom.
Compounds containing a chain of two isoprene units.
Terpenes with three consecutive isoprene units.
Terpene compounds formed by four isoprene units.
Terpenes composed of five consecutive isoprene units.
Terpene molecules containing 8 isoprene units.
Terpenoid molecules containing 10 consecutively linked isoprene units.
Steroid lactones containing a furan-2-one moiety linked to the C17 atom of a cyclopenta[a]phenanthrene derivative.
Glycerol-2-phosphates in which the glycerol moiety is bonded to two aliphatic chains through ester linkages.
Steroid lactones containing a pyran-2-one moiety linked to the C17 atom of a cyclopenta[a]phenanthrene derivative.
Bufanolides that are glycosidically linked to a glucose moiety.
Compounds containing a carbohydrate glycosidically bound to the cardenolide moiety.
C28 steroids structurally characterized by an ergostane skeleton usually functionalized at carbons 1, 22 and 26 to form a lactone ring.
Withanolides in which at least one hydroxyl group is glycosylated.
Compounds containing a dihydropyridine moiety bearing a carboxylic acid group.
Monoterpenoids containing 1 ring in the isoprene chain.
Monoterpenoids containing exactly 2 rings, which are fused to each other.

Monoterpenes containing a skeleton structurally characterized by the presence of a cylopentane fused to a pyran ( forming a 4,7-dimethylcyclopenta[c]pyran), or a derivative where the pentane moiety is open.
Hydrocarbons containing an alkene and an alkyne group.
Neurotoxic alkaloids, containing a 8-methyl-octahydroindolizin-8-ol or 1-methyl-octahydro-1H-quinolizin-1-ol moiety.
Inorganic compounds of miscellaneous structure, which can be a mixture of chemical elements of different types.
Inorganic compounds containing a phosphorotrithioic acid group, with the structure OP(S)(S)=S (or SP(S)(S)=O).
Organic compounds containing the organophosphorotrithioic acid structure or a derivative thereof. They have the general structure ROP(=S)(SR')SR\", where R-R\"= any atom.
Organic compounds containing the thiophosphoric acid amide functional group RN(R')OP(O)(O)=S, R,R'=H, alkyl, or aryl group.
Organic compounds containing the thiophosphoric acid functional group or a derivative thereof, with the general structure ROP(OR')(OR'')=S, where at least one R-group is an organyl group.
Organic compounds containing the thiophosphoric acid halide functional group, with the general structure RP(R')(X)=S, where R,R',R'' = O,N and X = halogen group.
Organic compounds containing phosphoric acid, with the general structure OP(O)(=O)O.
Ester derivatives of retinoic acid. These are obtained by formal condensation of the hydroxy group of retinol with the carboxy group of any carboxylic acid.
Organic compounds containing an alcohol group attached to the allyl functional group CH2=CHCH2.
Organic compounds containing the hyponitrite oxoanion, with the formula ([ON=NO]2-.
Organic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to a furanone.
Compounds containing a cyclohexene or cyclohexadiene ring that bears two methylidene groups.
Triterpenoids in which an isoprene unit is glycosylated.
Compounds containing a piperidine ring which bears a ketone.
Compounds containing a piperidine ring which bears two ketones.
Compounds containing a carbohydrate moiety which is O-glycosidically linked to the 2-phenylchromen-4-one flavonoid backbone.
Compounds containing a catechin moiety, which is a 3,4-dihydro-2-chromene-3,5.7-tiol.
Compounds containing the sulfonamide functional group, an amide of sulfonic acid with the general structure R1S(=O)2N(R2)R3 (R1=alkyl, aryl; R2,R3=H, alkyl, aryl).
Organic compounds containing at least two flavan/flavone units. These units are usually linked through CC or C-O-C bonds. Some examples include C2-O-C3, C2-O-C4, C3'-C3''', and C6-C8''.
Organic compounds containing a gallate moiety glycosidically linked to a catechin.
Lysine derivatives containing an acyl group linked to the N-epsilon atom of lysine.
Organic compounds containing the hypophosphite oxoanion, with the formula PO2−.
Organic compounds containing the iodate oxoanion, with the formula IO3-.
Inorganic compounds containing the sulfuryl bromide functional group, with the general structure BrS(R)(=O)=O (R=hetero atom).
Compounds containing a 3-hydroxy-2,4-dimethoxyphenyl linked to the C2 atom of a benzofuran moiety.
Organic compounds containing a dicarboxylic acyclic tetrapyrrole derivative.
Compounds containing epigallocatechin or a derivative. Epigallocatechin is a flavan-3-ol containing a benzopyran-3,5,7-triol linked to a 3,4,5-hydroxyphenyl moiety.
Diterpenoids with a structure based on the spatane or 4,10-secospatane skeleton. The spatane skeleton is formally derived from a prenylgermacrane by 1,5- and 6,10-cyclisation.
Sesterterpenoids (compounds made of five consecutive isoprene units) that do not contain a cycle.
Monoacylglycerols containing a glycerol acylated at the 1-position.
Compounds containing a hydroxyanthraquinone moiety, which consists of an anthracene bearing a quinone, and hydroxyl group.
Disaccharides carrying  one or more phosphate group on a sugar unit.
Organic compounds containing an anthraquinone moiety glycosidically bound to a carbohydrate moiety.
Cyclic depsipeptides containing the cyclosporin backbone.
Organic compounds containing a benzene ring conjugated to two methylidene groups at carbon atoms 1 and 3, respectively.
Monoacylglycerols containing a glycerol acylated at the 2-position.
Lignans with a structure that contains a tetrahydrofuran ring that arises from the joining of the two phenylpropanoid units.
Organic compounds containing two hydroxyl groups attached to a carbon atom.
Oxygenated derivatives of 3,7-dimethyl-1-(2,6,6-trimethylcyclohex-1-enyl)nona-1,3,5,7-tetraene and derivatives thereof.

Phenolic compounds containing a cis-fused tetrahydrochromeno[3,4-b]chromene nucleus. Many rotenoids contain an additional ring, e.g. rotenone. They are isoflavonoids characterized by the presence of an extra carbon atom in an additional heterocyclic ring.
Benzo-pyrano-furano-benzene compounds, containing the  6H-[1]benzofuro[3,2-c]chromene skeleton. They are derivatives of isoflavonoids.
Organic compounds containing the quaternary ammonium compound carnitine.

Lignans containing the arylnaphthalene skeleton, especially 9-(2H-1,3-benzodioxol-5-yl)-1H,3H-naphtho[2,3-c]furan-1-one or a derivative thereof. Arylnaphthalene lignans occur in nature and exhibit diverse biological activities.
Compounds comprising the carbonic acid diester functional group.
Polycyclic compounds with a structure based on the 3-phenyl-3,4-dihydro-2H-1-benzopyran skeleton.
Lignan compounds containing a 3,4-dibenzyloxolan-2-one moiety.
Compounds with a structure based on the 4-phenylchromene backbone.
Flavonoids with a structure based on the backbone of 2-phenylchromen-4-one (2-phenyl-1-benzopyran-4-one).
Inorganic compounds in which the largest oxoanion is nitrite, and in which the heaviest atom not in an oxoanion is a transition metal.
Nucleotides consisting of a purine base linked to a ribose to which one monophosphate group is attached.
Purine ribobucleotides with diphosphate group linked to the ribose moiety.
Purine ribobucleotides with a triphosphate group  linked to the ribose moiety.
Pyrimidine ribobucleotides with monophosphate group  linked to the ribose moiety.
Pyrimidine ribonucleotides with diphosphate group  linked to the ribose moiety.
Pyrimidine ribobucleotides with triphosphate group  linked to the ribose moiety.
Compounds containing a dibenzocyclooctadiene moiety, which consists of two hydroxylated benzene connected by a cycloheptene ring.
Lignan compounds containing a 2,3-dibenzylbutane-1,4-diol moiety.
Lignans with a structure containing the 1-aryltetralin skeleton, where the C9 and C9' atoms are joined to an oxygen atom to form a cyclopentanone.
Aromatic polycyclic compounds containing the phenanthroline skeleton, which is a derivative of phenanthrene, and consists of two pyridine rings non-linearly joined by a benzene ring.
Purine ribobucleotides with polyphosphate (with 4 or more phosphate) group linked to the ribose moiety.
Pyrimidine ribobucleotides with polyphosphate (with 4 or more phosphate) group  linked to the ribose moiety.
Organic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to a pyrazole ring. Pyrazole is a 5-membered ring consisting of three carbon atoms and two adjacent nitrogen centers.
Organic compounds containing 1,3-Diphenylpropenone (benzylideneacetophenone), ArCH=CH(=O)Ar, or its derivatives formed by substitution.
Flavonoids containing a 2-Benzylidene-1-benzofuran-3-one based core. Aurone flavonoids provide the bright yellow color of some important ornamental flowers, such as snapdragon (Antirrhinum majus).
Compounds containing a flavan-3-one moiety, with a structure characterized by a 2-phenyl-3,4-dihydro-2H-1-benzopyran bearing a ketone at the carbon C3.
Homoisoflavonoids with a structure based on the chromone system. Chromone is a bicyclic compound consisting of a 1-benzopyran, which bears a ketone group at the 4-position.

Compounds containing a furan ring fused to a naphthalene moiety. Furan is a 5 membered- ring aromatic ring with four carbon and one oxygen atoms. Naphthalene is a polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon  made up of two fused benzene rings.
Pyridoxals (or derivative) containing a phosphate linked to the carbaldehyde group.
Inorganic compounds containing the sulfuryl chloride functional group, with the general structure ClS(R)(=O)=O (R=hetero atom).
Compounds containing a serotonin moiety, which consists of an indole that bears an aminoethyl a position 2 and a hydroxyl group at position 5.
Glycerophosphocholines in which the glycerol is esterified with a fatty acid at O-1 position, and linked at position 3 to a phosphocholine.
Compounds structurally characterized by the presence of the tetrodotoxin skeleton, which is based on 5,7-(epoxymethanooxy)quinazolin-10-olate moiety.

Compounds containing a pyran ring fused to a naphthalene moiety. Furan is a 6 membered-ring non-aromatic ring with five carbon and one oxygen atoms. Naphthalene is a polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon  made up of two fused benzene rings.
Compounds containing a naphthopyran skeleton where a ring carbon bears a carboxylic acid group. Naphthtopyran is made up of the pyran ring fused to a naphthalene ring system.
Inorganic compounds containing the sulfuryl fluoride functional group, with the general structure FS(R)(=O)=O (R=hetero atom).
Glycerophosphocholines in which the glycerol is esterified with a fatty acid at O-2 position, and linked at position 3 to a phosphocholine.
Diacylglycerols containing a glycerol acylated at positions 1 and 2.

Polycyclic compounds that is either a polyphenolic compound composed of two or more monocyclic aromatic units linked by an ester bond (depside), or a compound containing the depsidone structure (depsidone).
Compounds containing a carbohydrate moiety glycosidically linked to a naphthopyranone moiety.
Diacylglycerols containing a glycerol acylated at positions 1 and 3.
Tyrosol derivatives in the hydroxyl group of the hydroxyethyl moiety is replaced an o-ester group.
Polycyclic compounds containing an isochromanequinone, which is structurally characterized by a quinone fused to an isochromane, and forming a naphtho[2,3-c]pyran-6,9-dione skeleton.
Compounds containing a tropone ring, which is a cycloheptatrienone ring bearing a ketone group.
Coenzymes containing a 2-amino-pteridine-4-one derivative. They are mainly synthesized in several parts of the body, including the pineal gland.
Compounds comprising the carbonic acid ester halide functional group.
Acyl CoAs where the group acylated to the coenzyme A moiety is a long aliphatic chain of 13 to 21 carbon atoms.
Aromatic compounds containing an esterified benzyl group.
Compounds comprising the carbonic acid monoester functional group.

Compounds having the structure R2C(OR')2 ( R' not Hydrogen) and thus diethers of geminal diols. Originally, the term was confined to derivatives of aldehydes (one R = H), but it now applies equally to derivatives of ketones (neither R = H ). Mixed acetals have different R' groups.
Carboxylic acid derivatives containing two carbonyl groups where the carbon atoms are both linked to the same nitrogen atom.
Compounds comprising an N-substituted carboxylic acid imide group, with the general structure R1N(C(R2)=O)C(R3)=O (R2,R3=H, alkyl, aryl; R1=Anything but H).
Compounds comprising an N-unsubstituted carboxylic acid imide group, with the general structure R1N(C(R2)=O)C(R3)=O (R1,R2,R3=H, alkyl, aryl).
Organic compounds containing the cyanide functional group attached to an alkyl chain through an ester bond.
Compounds containing a secondary alcohol functional group, with the general structure HOC(R)(R') (R,R'=alkyl, aryl).
Compounds comprising primary carboxylic acid amide functional group, with the general structure RC(=O)NH2.
Compounds containing a secondary carboxylic acid amide functional group, with the general structure RC(=O)N(R')H (R,R'=alkyl, aryl).
Compounds containing an amide derivative of carboxylic acid, with the general structure RN(R1)C(R2)=O (R1-R2 any atom but H).
Deprotonated anions of enols. They have diverse forms with either of the general structure [R1]C([R2])=C([R3])[O-], RC([CH2-])=O, or R1C(R1)=COM (M=metal).
Compounds containing the thiohemiaminal group with the general structure R1SC(R2)(R3)N(R4)R5 (R1-R5=H, alkyl, aryl).
Carboxylic acid derivatives two hydroxyl groups attached to a carbon atom, which in turn is linked to a nitrogen atom(substituted or not).
Organic compounds comprising the diazonium functional group, with the general structure R-N=N+.
Ceramides bearing a long chain fatty acid.
Compounds in which a hydroxy group, -OH, is attached to a saturated carbon atom R3COH (R not H ).

Steroidal constituents of Physalis plants which possess an unusual 13,14-seco-16,24-cyclo-steroidal ring skeleton (where the bond that is normally present between the 13 and 14 positions in other steroids is broken while a new bond between positions 16 and 24 is formed).
Organic compounds containing the thiocarbonic acid structure or a derivative thereof.
Organic compounds bearing the ketimine functional group, with the general structure R2C=NR' ( R is not a hydrogen ).
Compounds containing tropone ring with a hydroxyl group at ring position 2.

Organic compounds containing an amicocyclitol moiety glycosidically linked to a carbohydrate moiety. There are two major classes of aminoglycosides containing a 2-streptamine core. They are called 4,5- and 4,6-disubstituted 2-deoxystreptamines.
Phosphatidylinositol bisphosphates in which the two phosphate groups are at C-4 and C-5 of the inositol moiety.
Glycerophoethanolamines in which the glycerol is esterified with a fatty acid at O-1 position, and linked at position 3 to a phosphoethanolamine.
Acyclic hydrocarbons (and by extension, derivatives formed by substitution) having two double bonds from one carbon atom to two others.
Cyclic hydrocarbons (and by extension, derivatives formed by substitution) having two double bonds from one carbon atom to two others.
Glycerophoethanolamines in which the glycerol is esterified with a fatty acid at O-2 position, and linked at position 3 to a phosphoethanolamine.
Monoacylglycerol-3-phosphoserines with a fatty acyl chain linked to the O1-atom of the glycerol moiety.
Monoacylglycerol-3-phosphoserines with a fatty acyl chain linked to the O2-atom of the glycerol moiety.
Monacylglyerophosphates in which the glycerol moiety is esterified at only position, and is attached to a phosphate group.
Monacylglyerophosphates in which the glycerol moiety is esterified at position 1 and attached to a phosphate group through the O-2 atom.
Lysophosphatidic acids where the glycerol is esterified with a fatty acid at O-1 position.

Polycyclic compounds containing the tetracyclic cucurbitane nucleus skeleton, 19-(10->9b)-abeo-10alanost-5-ene (also known as 9b-methyl-19-nor lanosta-5-ene), with a variety of oxygenation functionalities at different positions.
Polycyclic compounds containing a carbohydrate derivative glycosidically linked to a curcubitane nucleus.
Lysophosphatidic acids where the glycerol is esterified with a fatty acid at O-2 position.
1-Acylglycerophosphates in which a long-chain fatty acid is esterified to the glycerol moiety.
Carbohydrates containing more than 10 sugar units, one of which bear one or more phosphate groups.
Compounds containing a steroid moiety which bears a carboxylic acid ester group.
Sterol lipids containing a sulfate group attached to the steroid skeleton.
Organic compounds containing an amino group attached to a triazine ring.
Organic compounds containing an amino group attached to a pyrazine ring.
Sugar amino acids containing an oxetane ring between the carboxy- and the amino terminals of the amino acid chain.
Sugar amino acids containing a furan ring.
Compounds containing a (hydro)pyran ring bearing unprotected amino and carboxylic acid functionalities.
Sugar amino acids in which the amino acid is attached to or partly borne within a bicyclic ring system.
Compounds in which a carbohydrate component is linked to a peptide through any covalent bond.

Steroidal alkaloids with a structure containing a spirostane skeleton. Spirostanes are 16b,22:22,26-diepoxycholestanes, or 22,26-epoxyfurostans. The sixth ring so formed is known as ring F. Chemically, the spiro centre at C-22 has the character of an internal acetal derived from a 16b, 26-dihydroxycholestan-22-one.
Compounds containing or derived from the steroid parent furostane, which is a 16b,22-epoxycholestane derivative, the extra ring being labeled as\nring E.
Heterocyclic steroids containing a furospirostane moiety, which a skeleton characterized by the presence of a 1,6-dioxaspiro[4.4]nonane ring system and an androstane moiety.
Steroids with a structure based on the solanidane skeleton.  Solanidane arises from the conversion of a cholestane side-chain into a bicyclic system.

Steroidal alkaloids with a structure containing a spirosolane skeleton. Siporosolane is a polycyclic compound that is characterized by a 1-oxa-6-azaspiro[4.5]decane moiety where the oxolane ring is fused to a docosahydronaphth[2,1:4',5']indene ring system. Spirosolane arises from the conversion of a cholestane side-chain into a bicyclic system containing a piperidine and a tetrahydrofuran ring.
Compounds containing a gingerol moiety, which is structurally characterized by a 4-hydroxy-3-methoxyphenyl group substituted at the C6 carbon atom by a 5-hydroxy-alkane-3-one.
Compounds containing a gingerdiol moiety, which is structurally characterized by a 4-hydroxy-3-methoxyphenyl group substituted at the C6 carbon atom by an alkane-2,4-diol.
Compounds containing a gingerdione moiety, which is structurally characterized by a 4-hydroxy-3-methoxyphenyl group substituted at the C6 carbon atom by an alkane-2,4-dione.
Ginger derivatives containing a shogaol moiety, which consists of a benzene ring bearing a dec-4-en-3-one moiety, a methoxyphenyl group, a hydroxyl group and at positions 1, 3, and 4, respectively.
Compounds containing a paradol moiety, which is consists of a benzene ring with a decan-3-one moiety, a methoxyl group, and a hydroxyl group at positions 1,3, and 4 respectively.

Tannins with a structure characterized by either of the following models. In model 1, the structure contains galloyl units (in some cases, shikimic acid units) that are linked to diverse polyol carbohydrate-, catechin-, or triterpenoid units. In model 2, contains at least two galloyl units C-C coupled to each other, and do not contain a glycosidically linked catechin unit.
Tannins which is formed by oligomerization of phloroglucinol. Phloroglucinol is an aromatic compound, which consists of a benzene ring bearing one hydroxyl group at the 1-,3-, and 5-positions.
Tannins made of a catechin bound to a gallotannin or elagitannin.
Compounds containing a carboxylic acid substituted with a hydroxyl group on the C3 carbon atom.
Compounds containing a quinoline moiety bearing a hydroxyl group and a ketone. Quinoline or benzo[b]pyridine is a bicyclic compound that consists of benzene fused to a pyridine.
Derivatives of  quinoline in which in which at least one double bond in the quinoline moiety are reduced by adding two hydrogen atoms.
Compounds containing a hydrogenated quinoline bearing a ketone group.
Compounds containing a six-member aliphatic heterocycle made up of one oxygen atom, a boron atom, and three carbon atoms.
Glycerophosphoinositol phosphates not belonging to Lysophosphatidylinositol Phosphates, or the Phosphatidylinositol Phosphates.
Glycerophosphodiradylglycerols that carry exactly two acyl chains attached to the glycerol moiety through ester linkages.
Glycerophosphates (molecules containing a phosphate group linked to a glycerol) where the glycerol is esterified with one fatty acid.
Sphingolipids containing a carbohydrate linked to the sphingoid base (sphingosine, sphinganine) through a phosphate group.
Ester derivatives of a fatty alcohol.
Mixtures of long-chain apolar lipids. They are usually esters of an alcohol other than glycerol and a long chain acid.
Pyrethroids with a structure based on a skeleton that is characterized by the presence of a chrysanthemic acid esterified with a cyclopentenone derivative.
Compounds containing an ester derivative of chloropropanol.
Compounds containing a 3-monochloropropane-1,2-diol skeleton that is esterified either at the C1 or C3 terminal carbon atom only.
Glycosylglycerophospholipids, where the glycerol moiety is esterified with two fatty acyl chains.
Compounds containing a quinacridine moiety, which consists of a quinoline fused to an acridine.
Compounds containing an oxepane ring, which is a seven-member saturated aliphatic heterocycle with one oxygen and six carbon atoms.
Compounds containing a piperidinylpyridine moiety, which consists of a piperidine linked to a pyridine by a single bond that is not pat of a ring.
Compounds containing a piperazine ring bearing two ketone groups. These include the alkaloid class of naturally occurring 2,5-dioxopiperazines.
Compounds containing a piperazine ring which bears two ketone groups and a sulfanyl group.

Compounds containing a pyrroloindole moiety, which is a tricyclic heterocycle which consists of a pyrrole ring fused to an indole. Pyrrole is 5-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and one nitrogen atom. Indole is a bicyclic  compound consisting of a six-membered benzene ring fused to a five-membered nitrogen-containing pyrrole ring.
Compounds containing a pyrroloquinoline moiety, which consists of a pyrrole ring fused to a quinoline.
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing a furan ring fused to a 1-benzopyran-4-one ring system.
Organic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to the benzene moiety of chromone (1,4-benzopyrone).
Compounds containing a carbohydrate moiety which is C-glycosidically linked to the 2-phenylchromen-4-one flavonoid backbone.
Aurone flavonoids containing a carbohydrate moiety O-glycosidically bound to the aurone skeleton.
Compounds containing a O-glycosylated chalcone or dihydrochalcone moiety.
Organic compounds containing the antimonate oxoanion, with the formula Sb(OH)6-.
Compounds containing a carbohydrate moiety glycosidically linked to the rotenoid backbone at the C8-position.
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing a 1-benzopyran-4-one and a benzofuran, where the furan ring and the pyran ring are fused together.
Aromatic compounds containing a carbohydrate moiety glycosidically bound to a coumarin moiety.

Lipids containing a five-carbon backbone that comprises a nitrile moiety together with a methylene group or double bond, and one or two hydroxyl groups. Cyanolipids are divided in four categories (type I-IV).
Diesters of 1-cyano-2-hydroxymethylprop-2-en-1-ol.
Diesters of 1-cyano-2-hydroxymethylprop-1-en-3-ol.
Monoesters of 1-cyano-2-hydroxymethylprop-1-ene.
Monoesters of 1-cyano-2-methylprop-2-en-1-ol.
Lipids with a structure based on a bis(monoacylglycero)phosphate skeleton.
Bisphosphatidic acid analogues with three moles of fatty acid per mole of lipid.
Organic compounds containing two 1,2-diacylglycerol moieties linked to the O1 and O4 oxygen atoms of a phosphate group.
Purine nucleotides in which the atom linked to the C2 carbon atom of the ribose moiety is bonded the C8 carbon atom of the purine moiety.
Organic compounds containing an indole attached to a benzoyl moiety through the acyl group.
Glycolipids composed of a long chain secondary alcohol glycosylated by an alpha-D-glucosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-galactosyl disaccharide residue.
Diterpenoids in which an isoprene unit is glycosylated.
Prenol lipids containing a carbohydrate moiety glycosidically linked to a steviol (a diterpenoid based on a 13-Hydroxykaur-16-en-18-oic acid) moiety.
Diterpenoids with a structure based on the clerodane or the colensane skeleton. Clerodanes arise from labdanes by two methyl migrations.
Quinone derivatives containing a dalbergione moiety, which consists of a 1-4 quinone conjugated to a phenyl group  at ring carbon 2.
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing a furan ring fused to a flavan-3-one.
Diterpenoids with a structure based on the dolabellane skeleton (3a,6,10-trimethyl-1-(propan-2-yl)-cyclopenta[11]annulene) or the neodolabellane skeleton.
Lactones, which is structurally characterized by a benzene ring and a pyranone moiety, linked to each other to form a 4-methoxy-6-(2-phenylethyl)-2H-pyran-2-one skeleton.
Compounds containing a pyrroloacridine moiety, which is a tetracyclic heterocycle which consists of a pyrrole ring fused to an acridine.
Compounds containing a pyridoacridine ring system, which consists of a pyridine fused to an acridine.
Compounds containing a pyridinium ring, which is the cationic form of pyridine.
Glycolipids structurally characterized by a glycosyl head group, in this case a rhamnose moiety, and a 3-(hydroxyalkanoyloxy)alkanoic acid (HAA) fatty acid tail.

Compounds containing fatty acyl chain linked to a carbohydrate moiety through a glycosidic bond. Fatty acyl glycosides are composed of a glycosyl moiety (one or several units) linked to one hydroxyl group of a fatty alcohol or of a phosphorylated alcohol (phosphoprenols), a hydroxy fatty acid or to one carboxyl group of a fatty acid (ester linkage) or to an amino alcohol.
Diterpenoids containing the gibberellane skeleton ((8S)-4,4,8-trimethyl-13-methylidenetetracyclo[10.2.1.0^{1,9}.0^{3,8}]pentadecane), an aliphatic four-ring system.

Diterpene lactones with a structure based either on the gingkolide or the bilobalide skeleton. The ginkgolide skeleton is a very rigid structure consisting of hexacyclic C20 trilactone. The cis-fused F/A/D/C ring junction forms an empty semi-ball hole, the D ring contains a cage form tetrahydrofuran ring which occupies the center of the empty hole, and the oxygen atoms of the D,C and F ring and 10-hydroxyl group consist of an analogous crown ether structure.
Compounds containing a pyrroloindolizine moiety, which consists of a pyrrole ring fused to an indolizine.
Diterpene lactones with a structure characterized by the presence of a gamma-lactone fused to a guaiane, forming 3,6,9-trimethyl-azuleno[4,5-b]furan-2-one or a derivative.
Sesquiterpene lactones with a structure based on the germacranolide skeleton, characterized by a gamma lactone fused to a 1,7-dimethylcyclodec-1-ene moiety.

Terpenoids with a structure based on the eudesmanolide (a 3,5a,9-trimethyl-naphtho[1,2-b]furan-2-one derivative) or secoeudesmanolide (a 3,6-dimethyl-5-(pentan-2-yl)-1-benzofuran-2-one derivative) skeleton.
Glycosylglycerols carrying exactly one fatty acyl chain attached to the glycerol moiety through an ester linkage.
Cholestane based steroid lactones containing benzo[c]indeno[5,4-e]oxepin-3-one.

Isoquinoline alkaloids with a skeleton deriving from lycorine, norbelladine, homolycorine, hemanthamine, crinine, tazettine, montanine, plicamine, galanthindole, galanthamine, gracilline, among others. Amaryllidaceae Alkaloids represent a large group of biogenetically related isoquinoline alkaloids that are found exclusively in plants belonging to this family of Amaryllidaceae. This group of alkaloids is also derived from two tyrosine units which combine, with loss of one carbon atom, to give a benzylphenylethylamine precursor unit, e.g. Norbelladine, which by various oxidative cyclisation processes, prominent among which are phenol oxidative coupling reactions, can give rise to the nine major skeletal groups.
Compounds with a structure characterized by the presence of a 2-hydroxy-4-methoxy-6-methylbenzoic acid derivative linked to a 3,6,6,7b-tetramethyl-cyclobuta[e]indene moiety.

Sesquiterpenoids containing either the illudane moiety (based on a 3,6,6,7b-tetramethyl-decahydro-1H-cyclobuta[e]indene ring system), the illudin moiety (2',2',4',6'-tetramethyl-octahydrospiro[cyclopropane-1,5'-indene]), or a derivative thereof.
Compounds containing a benzene ring conjugated to two methylidene groups at carbon atoms 1 and 2, respectively.
Aromatic compounds containing a guanidine group linked to the benzene ring of a benzoic acid (or a derivative thereof).
Organic heterocyclic compounds with a structure based on the dihydrofuranoquinoline skeleton.

Sesquiterpenoids with a structure based on an aromadendrane (a cyclopropa[e]azulene derivative) skeleton. Some aromadendrane sesquiterpenoids are found in essential oils. Certain aromadendrane Sesquiterpenoids from the Leaves of Xylopia brasiliensis were found to possess antifungal activities.
Organic compounds with a structure based on a backbone containing a indole-6-ol sharing its nitrogen atom with an isoquinoline ring system.
Compounds containing the pentacyclic curan skeleton, which is structurally characterized by the presence of a pentacyclic 3,5-ethanopyrrolo[2,3-d]carbazole framework.
Ergoline analogues, obtained by replacing the oxygen atom in the indole moiety (of the ergoline backbone) by a sulfur atom.
Polycyclic compounds with a four-ring skeleton with three condensed six-member rings forming a partially hydrogenated naphthopyran moiety, one of which is aromatic while the two others are alicyclic.
Alkaloids containing the pentacyclic yohimban skeleton. The Yohimbinoid alkaloids contain a carbocyclic ring E arising through C-17 to C-18 bond formation in a corynantheine precursor.
A group of chemically related metabolites containing a 3,4-dihydro-3-methylisocoumarin moiety linked through a carboxyl group to L-beta-phenylalanine by a secondary amine bond.
Macrolides which contains a fourteen-member lactone fused to 1,3-dihydroxybenzene.

Sesquiterpene mycotoxins structurally characterized by the presence of an epoxide ring and a benzopyran derivative with a variant number of hydroxyl, acetyl, or other substituents. The most important structural features causing the biological activities of trichothecenes are the 12,13-epoxy ring, the presence of hydroxyl or acetyl groups at appropriate positions on the trichothecene nucleus and the structure and position of the side-chain.

Compounds containing an epipolythiodioxopiperazine moiety, which consists of a 2,3-dithia-5,7-diazabicyclo[2.2.2]octane-6,8-dione ring system. One distinct characteristics of Epipolythiodioxopiperazines is the presence of unique di- or polysulfide bridges.
Polycyclic compounds containing the gliotoxin skeleton, which is structurally characterized by a epipolythiodioxopiperazine moiety fused to the pyrrolidine ring of an indol-7-ol derivative.

Diesters of propane-1,2,3-tricarboxylic acid (TCA) and similar long-chain aminopolyol backbones (for FB1: 2S-amino-12S,16R-dimethyl-3S,5R,10R,14S,15R-pentahydroxyeicosane). Structurally, fumonisins resemble the sphingoid bases sphinganine (SA) and sphingosine (SO) to which TCA groups have been added at the C-14 and C-15 positions.
Compounds containing a pyrido[4,3-b]carbazole moiety.

Organic compounds containing either of the ajmalan, sarpagan skeleton, or derivative thereof. The Sarpagine (Akuammidine) group, based on the sarpagan nucleus, arises from bond formation between C-16 and C-5 of the corynantheine precursor.  Ajmaline alkaloids are based on a 17,19-secoyohimban skeleton (oxayohimban) which is invariably present as an ether.
Alkaloids with a structure based on either sparteine, lupanine, or derivatives thereof. These are tetracyclic compounds made of two fused quinolizidine ring systems.
Compounds containing an oxocin ring, which is a eight-member unsaturated aromatic ring containing one oxygen atom and seven carbon atoms.

Organic polycyclic compounds containing an imidazole ring fused to a pyrimidine ring. Imidazole is 5-membered ring consisting of three carbon atoms, and two nitrogen centers at the 1- and 3-positions. Pyrimidine is a 6-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and two nitrogen centers at the 1- and 3- ring positions.

Compounds containing a pyrrolotriazine moiety, which consists of a pyrrole ring fused to a triazine ring. Pyrrole is 5-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and one nitrogen atom. Triazine is a 6-membered ring consisting of three carbon atoms and three nitrogen centers.

Compounds containing a pyrrolopyrimidine moiety, which consists of a pyrrole ring fused to a pyrimidine. Pyrrole is 5-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and one nitrogen atom. Pyrimidine is a 6-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and two nitrogen centers at the 1- and 3- ring positions.
Compounds with a structure based on a 2,6-diamino-4-methyl-pyrrolo[1,2-c]purin-10-ol skeleton.
Non-proteigenous amino acids with a structure characterized by the presence of a pyrrolidine ring bearing two dicarboxylic acid groups.
Marine heterocyclic polyethers containing the okadaic acid skeleton.
A group of poly-ether-lactone toxins.
Organic compounds containing the pyrophosphate oxoanion, with the structure OP([O-])(=O)OP(O)([O-])=O.
Compounds containing a quinuclidine moiety which bears a ketone group.
Organic compounds containing the arsenate oxoanion, with the formula AsO43-.
Steroid lactones with a structure based on the spironolactone skeleton.
Lipid-soluble polyether compounds consisting of 13 to 14 rings fused by ether linkages into a most rigid ladder-like structure.
Compounds containing a quinacridone skeleton, which consists of a quinoline fused to an acridone.
Pyridoacridines with a structure that contains an acridine moiety bearing a ketone. Acridine is a linear tricyclic heterocycle which consists of two benzene rings joined by a pyridine ring.
Acridines containing a ketone group attached to the C9 carbon atom of the acridine moiety.
Compounds consisting of saccharide linked through a glycosyl linkage (O-, N-, or S-) to an amino acid.
Compounds containing non-peptidic structural elements that is capable of mimicking or antagonizing the biological action(s) of a natural parent peptide.
Compounds containing a phenylphosphine, which consists of phosphine substituent bound to a phenyl group.
Compounds in which a carbohydrate component is linked to a peptidomimetic component.
Organic compounds containing a two furan rings fused to each other. Furan is a five-membered aromatic ring with four carbon atoms and one oxygen atom.

A group of closely related fungal metabolites chemically characterized by a xanthone moiety fused to a dihydrodifurano or a tetrahydrodifurano moiety. The chemical difference among the various sterigmagocystins are the presence or absence of unsaturation at positions 2 and 3 of the difurano ring system, the substitution pattern on positions 6, 7, and 10 of the xanthone system and/or the substituent on position 3 of the difurano system. They are produced by Aspergilus spp. and Bipolaris spp.

Organic polycyclic compounds containing a furan ring fused to a pyran ring. Furan is a five-membered aromatic ring with four carbon atoms and one oxygen atom. Pyran a six-membered heterocyclic, non-aromatic ring, made up of five carbon atoms and one oxygen atom and containing two double bonds.
Polycyclic compounds containing an isoindole moiety, which is structurally characterized by a cyclohexadiene fused to a pyrrole ring.
Aromatic polycyclic compounds that an isoindole bearing a ketone.

Fungal metabolites structurally characterized by the presence of an isoindolone nucleus fused to a macrocyclic ring, which can either a lactone, as in cytochalasin B, a carbonate, as in cytochalasin E, or a carbocycle, as in cytochalasin D,  H, and K.
Organic compounds containing an oxadiazole ring, which is a five-member aromatic heterocycle with two nitrogen atoms, an oxygen atom, and a carbon atom.
Terpenoids containing hopane skeleton(A'-Neogammacerane), a pentacyclic structure with four cyclohexane rings and one cyclopentane ring (and often, a side chain emerging from C30).
Triterpenoids with a structure based on the hopane skeleton.
Terpenoids consisting of more than eight isoprene units.
Bacterial terpenoids structurally characterized by a C30 skeleton, which is usually conjugated to a C5 (usually hydroxylated) unit linked by a carbon-carbon bond.
Polycyclic compounds containing an isoflavan skeleton which bears a ketone at position C4.
Polycyclic compounds containing a hydroxylated isoflavan skeleton.
Terphenyls with a structure containing the 1,3-diphenylbenzene skeleton.
Inorganic compounds containing the sulfuryl fluoride functional group, with the general structure IS(R)(=O)=O (R=hetero atom).
Organic compounds containing a carbonyl group, with the general structure RC(=O)R', where R=organyl, R'=H, N, O, organyl group or halide group.
Organic compounds containing a functional group with the general formula R1(R2)C=S-NR3 (R1,R3=alkyl, aryl; R2=H, alkyl, aryl).

Heterocyclic compounds containing a thiophene ring fused to a pyrrole ring. Thiophene is 5-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and one sulfur atom. Pyrrole is 5-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and one nitrogen atom.

Compounds containing a pyrrolothiazole moiety, which consists of a pyrrole ring fused to a thiazole ring. Pyrrole is 5-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and one nitrogen atom. Thiazole is a 6-membered ring that contains both sulfur and nitrogen.
Compounds containing a pyrrolizidine moiety which bears an oxime group at ring position 1. Pyrrolizidine is a bicyclic ring system made up of two fused pyrrolidine ring sharing a nitrogen atom.
Terphenyls with a structure containing the 1,2-diphenylbenzene skeleton.
Organic compounds containing the peroxynitrate oxoanion, with the formula [NO4]−.
Organic compounds containing the peroxonitrite oxoanion, with the formula  ONOO-.
Organic compounds containing an aluminate oxoanion, with the formula [AlO2]-.
Organic compounds containing a stannate oxoanion, with the formula [SnO3]2-.
Organic compounds containing the orthovanadate oxoanion, with the formula [VO4]3-.
Organic compounds containing a tetrazolidine ring, which is a five-member saturated aliphatic heterocycle made up of four nitrogen atoms and a one carbon atom.
Compounds containing a phenyltetrazoline skeleton, which consists of a tetrazoline bound to a phenyl group.

Non-conventional lignans that derived from flavonoids. They are characterized by a p-dioxin ring substituted at one carbon atom by a C3C6 (phenylpropan) group and fused to the B-ring of the 2-phenylchromene moiety.
Compounds that contain two benzene groups linked to each other via an ether bond, and where at least one ring is substituted with a bromo group.
Organic compounds containing an acetamide group conjugated to a phenyl group.
Glycerophosphocholines that carry exactly one 1Z-alkenyl chain attached at the O1 position of a glycerol moiety through an ether linkage.
Organic peptide derivatives with monosaccharide units linked through Phosphate diester bonds.
Oligosaccharides having carbohydrate subunits linked to one another by amide bonds.
Compounds containing a thiophenol ring, which a phenol derivative obtained by replacing the oxygen atom from the hydroxyl group (attached to the benzene) by a sulfur atom.
Compounds containing a pyrene moiety, which consists four fused benzene rings, resulting in a flat aromatic system.
Organic compounds containing an alkyl chain with an amine group bound to the C1 atom and an alcohol group bound to the C3 atom.
Compounds containing a six-member aliphatic saturated heterocycle made up of three oxygen atoms and three carbon atoms.
Compounds containing a five-member aliphatic saturated heterocycle made up of three oxygen atoms and two carbon atoms.
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing a phenoxazine moiety, which is a linear tricyclic system that consists of a two benzene rings joined by a 1,4-oxazine ring.
Compounds containing a pyridazinoindazole moiety, which consists of a pyridazine ring fused to an indazole.

Compounds containing a naphthyridine moiety, a naphthalene in which a carbon atom has been replaced by a nitrogen in each of the two rings. The naphthyridine skeleton can also be described as an assembly two fused pyridine rings, which do not share their nitrogen atom.
Compounds containing a naphthyridine moiety, where one of the ring atoms bears a carboxylic acid group.

Compounds containing a pyridopyrimidine, which consists of a pyridine fused to a pyrimidine. Pyridine is 6-membered ring consisting of five carbon atoms and a nitrogen atom. Pyrimidine is a 6-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and two nitrogen centers at the 1- and 3- ring positions.
Pyridopyrimidines with a structure that contains pyrimidine moiety bearing a carboxylic acid group, and a pyridine ring fused to the pyrimidine.
Heterocyclic compounds containing a pyridine ring substituted by one or more sulfonamide groups.
Organic compounds containing a six-member aliphatic saturated heterocycle made up of three sulfur atoms and three carbon atoms.
Compounds containing a dithiane moiety, which is composed of a cyclohexane core structure wherein two methylene units are replaced by sulfur centres.
Compounds containing an oxirane ring bearing a carboxylic acid group (or a derivative thereof).
Compounds containing a pyrrolocarbazole moiety, which is a tetracyclic heterocycle which consists of a pyrrole ring fused to a carbazole.
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing an indole fused to a carbazole.

Nucleosides with a structure that consists of an  imidazole moiety of benzotriazole is N-linked to a ribose (or deoxyribose). Nucleotides have a phosphate group linked to the C5 carbon of the ribose (or deoxyribose) moiety.

Compounds in which the C-1 of a ribose (or deoxyribose)  is linked to the N1-position of the indazole ring. Nucleotides have a phosphate group linked to the C5 carbon of the ribose (or deoxyribose) moiety.

Compounds in which the C-1 of a ribosyl (or deoxyribosyl) moiety is linked to the N1-position of an indole. Nucleotides have a phosphate group linked to the C5 carbon of the ribose (or deoxyribose) moiety.
Compounds containing a naphthohydroquinone moiety, which consists of a benzene ring fused to a bezene-1,4-diol (hydroquinone).
Compounds containing a naphthalene moiety, which bears a carboxylic acid group or a derivative at one or more positions. Naphthalene is a bicyclic compound that is made up of two fused benzene ring.
Compounds containing a benzene ring conjugated to two methylidene groups at carbon atoms 1 and 4, respectively..
Compounds containing a 3-hydrocarbylidene-2-benzofuran-1(3H)-one moiety,.
Compounds containing a sulfonphthalide moiety, which consists of a benzene ring fused to an oxathiole-1,1-dione.
Organic compounds containing a benzene fused to an oxathiole ring (a five-membered ring with four carbon atoms, one oxygen atom, and one sulfur atom).
Organic compounds containing a carboxylic acid group (or a derivative thereof) attached to an azetidine ring.
Organic compounds containing a carboxylic acid group(or a derivative thereof) attached to an aziridine ring.
Amino acids having a (-NH2) group attached to the beta carbon atom.
Compounds containing a carboxylic acid group and an amino group at the C5 carbon atom.
Amino acids having a (-NH2) group attached to the gamma carbon atom.
Heterocyclic compounds containing a saturated four-member ring with two carbon atoms, one sulfur atom, and one nitrogen.
Organic compounds containing a sulfonamide group in which the N-S bond is part of a four member ring.
Organic compounds containing a gamma-sultam moiety, a five-member cyclic sulfonamide, containing the NS bond, and three carbon atoms.
Heterocyclic compounds containing a saturated six-member ring with four carbon atoms, one sulfur atom, and one nitrogen.
Cyclic organic compounds containing a 1,2-thiazinane-1,1-dione moiety.

Compounds containing an oxathietane moiety, which consists of a saturated aliphatic four-member ring with one oxygen atom, a sulfur atom, and two carbon atoms. Isomers  of oxaphospholane include 1,2-oxathietane, and 1,3-oxathietane.
Organic compounds containing a four-member cyclic ester of hydroxy sulfonic acid, analogous to lactones. Here, the O-S bond is part of the ring.
Organic compounds containing a gamma-sultone, a Intramolecular cyclic ester of hydroxy sulfonic acid, with a SO ring bond, and three ring carbon atoms.

Compounds containing an oxathiane moiety, which consists of a saturated aliphatic six-member ring with one oxygen atom, a sulfur atom, and four carbon atoms. Isomers  of oxaphospholane include 1,2-oxathiane, 1,3-oxathiane,and 1,4-oxathiane.
Polycyclic compounds containing an isochromane which bears a ketone at the carbon C1.
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing a sulfinyl group attached at the position 2 of a benzimidazole moiety.
Organic compounds containing an acetonitrile with one hydrogen replaced by a biphenyl group.
Aromatic compounds containing a halogen atom linked to a pyrimidine ring. Pyrimidine is a 6-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and two nitrogen centers at the 1- and 3- ring positions.
Heterocyclic compounds containing a saturated six-member ring with five carbon atoms and one sulfur atom.
Compounds containing a six-member aliphatic heterocycle made up of one sulfur atom and five carbon atoms.
Heterocyclic compounds containing a thiophene ring fused to a quinoline. Quinoline or benzo[b]pyridine is a bicyclic compound that consists of benzene fused to a pyridine.
Organic compounds containing an alkyl chain with an amine group bound to the C1 atom and an alcohol group bound to the C2 atom.
Organic compounds containing the triazene group (-N-N=N), which consists of an amine directly bonding to an azo group.
Compounds containing a cylindrospermopsin moiety, which contains a triazaacenaphthylene moiety linked to a pyrimidinedione.
Cyclic polyketides containing  both a cyclic amide and a cyclic ester group.

Peptide analogues containing two 2-sulfonylethan-1-amine groups linked together through a bond between the terminal nitrogen atom of one group and the sulfur atom (of the sulfonyl ) from the other group.

Peptide analogues containing a sulfonylmethanamine group and a 2-sulfonylethan-1-amine group linked together through a bond between the terminal nitrogen atom of one group and the sulfur atom (of the sulfonyl ) from the other group.

Compounds containing a pyrrolidine ring which bears a carboxylic acid or a derivative thereof. Pyrrolidine is a five-membered saturated aliphatic heterocycle with one nitrogen atom and four carbon atoms.
Pyrimidine ribobucleotides with one phosphate group attached to each of two different hydroxyl groups of the ribose moiety.
Compounds containing the sulfinylamine functional group, with the general structure RN=S=O.

Aromatic polycyclic compounds containing the phenanthroindolizidine skeleton, which is structurally characterized by an indolizidine and a phenanthrene, where the indolizidine is fused to the second benzene ring of a phenanthrene.

Aromatic polycyclic compounds containing the phenanthroindolizidine skeleton, which is structurally characterized by an indolizidine and a phenanthrene, where the quinolizidine is fused to the second benzene ring of a phenanthrene.
Organic compounds containing a benzene fused to a quinoline ring system.
Alkaloids with a structure based on a protoberberine moiety, which consists of a 5,6-dihydrodibenzene moiety fused to a quinolizinium and forming 5,6-Dihydrodibenzo(a,g)quinolizinium skeleton.
Organic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to an oxepine ring (an unsaturated seven-membered heterocycle with one oxygen atom replacing a carbon atom).
Organic compounds containing a carboxylic acid group (or a derivative thereof) attached to an anthracene ring system.
Compounds containing a pyridoisoindole, which consists of a pyridine fused to an isoindole.
Organic compounds containing a pyrido[2,3-b]indole core (which is a pyridine fused to an indole).
Compounds containing a 9H-pyrido[3,4-b]indole moiety.
Aromatic compounds containing a delta carboline moiety, which consists of a pyridine fused to and indole to form pyrido[3,2-b]indole.
Polycyclic aromatic compounds containing a gamma-carbazole(5H-pyrido[4,3-b]indole) moiety, with a structure characterized by the presence of pyridine fused to the pyrrole ring of an indole.
Organic compounds containing a benzamide moiety with an amine group attached to the benzene ring.

Organic polycyclic compounds containing a furan ring fused to a pyrrole ring. Furan is a five-membered aromatic ring with four carbon atoms and one oxygen atom. Pyrrole is 5-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and one nitrogen atom.
Heterocyclic compounds containing a thioketone group conjugated to a saturated six-member ring with four carbon atoms, one sulfur atom, and one nitrogen.
Compounds containing a triazine ring which bears a ketone group a carbon atom.
Compounds containing a pyrimidine ring that bears a thioketone. Pyrimidine is a 6-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and two nitrogen centers at the 1- and 3- ring positions.
Compounds containing a triazine ring which bears a thioketone group.
Heterocyclic compounds containing a thiazolidinethione ring which bears one thioketone group.
Organic compounds containing an amino group attached to a pyridazine ring.
Organic compounds containing a benzenesulfonamide moiety with an amine group attached to the benzene ring.
Polycyclic compounds containing a tetrapyrrole skeleton combined with a metal atom.
Compounds containing a pyrimidine ring which bears a nitro group. Pyrimidine is a 6-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and two nitrogen centers at the 1- and 3- ring positions.

Heterocyclic compounds containing a thiophene ring fused to a thiazine. Thiophene is 5-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and one sulfur atom. Thiazine is a 6-membered ring consisting of four carbon, one nitrogen and one sulfur atoms.

Heterocyclic compounds containing a thiophene ring fused to a thiazole. Thiophene is 5-membered ring consisting of four carbon atoms and one sulfur atom. Thiazole is a 6-membered ring that contains both sulfur and nitrogen.
Organic compounds containing a benzene fused to an oxadiazole ring (a five-membered ring with two carbon atoms, one nitrogen atom, and one oxygen atom).

Compounds containing an oxatriazole moiety, which consists of an unsaturated aliphatic five-member ring with one oxygen atom, three nitrogen, one carbon atom, and two double bonds. Isomers  of oxatriazole include 1,2,3,4-oxatriazole, and 1,2,3,5-oxatriazole.
Organic compounds containing an oxatriazolidine ring, which is a five-member saturated aliphatic heterocycle with three nitrogen atoms, an oxygen atom, and a carbon atom.
Organic compounds containing an oxadiazole ring, which is a five-member saturated aliphatic heterocycle with two nitrogen atoms, an oxygen atom, and two carbon atoms.
Derivatives of  pyridine in which two double bonds in the pyridine moiety are reduced by adding four hydrogen atoms.
Compounds containing a N-phenylurea moiety, which is structurally characterized by a phenyl group linked to one nitrogen atom of a urea group.
Organic compounds containing an amino group attached to a thiophene ring.
Compounds containing a polyisoprene chain attached to a quinol(hydroquinone) at the second ring position.

Peptidomimetics made of N-substituted amino acids, in which the side chains are attached to the nitrogen atom of the peptide backbone, rather than to the alpha-carbons. Alpha-peptoids (commonly referred to as peptoids) are N-substituted glycines. But in general, this class also extends to oligo- or polymers of beta-, gamma-, delta peptoid analogues of amino acids.
Compounds containing a peptoid-peptide backbone, which consists alternating amino acid and n-substituted amino acids linked to each other by a peptide bond.
Peptidomimetics structurally characterized by the presence of n-alkyl urea motifs linked in a repetitive manner.
Biomimetic oligomers consisting of alpha-amino acids linked in a repetitive manner.
Peptide analogues in which one or more of the amino residues is replaced by a semicarbazide.
Peptidomimetics containing a polyisoxazoline backbone, which consists of isoxazoline rings linked together forming several 3-(4,5-dihydro-1,2-oxazol-5-ylmethyl)-4,5-dihydro-1,2-oxazole units.
Compounds containing several thiourea groups linked to each other.

Peptide analogues containing two (2E)-3-sulfonylprop-2-en-1-amine groups linked together through a bond between the terminal nitrogen atom of one group and the sulfur atom (of the sulfonyl ) from the other group to form (1E)-3-amino-N-[(2E)-3-sulfonylprop-2-en-1-yl]prop-1-ene-1-sulfonamide.
Peptidomimetics made of  two (2E)-4-aminobut-2-enoic acid linked through a peptide bond.
Polycyclic aromatic peptidomimetics consisting of at least two imidazole rings connected by a carboxamide group to form a N-(1H-imidazol-4-yl)-1H-imidazole-2-carboxamide moiety.
Pyridoxal derivatives in which the carbaldehyde group at position 2 of the pyridoxal moiety is replaced by a hydroxymethyl group.
