Anthocyanidin 5-O-glycosides where the carbohydrate moiety is esterified at the C2 position with a p-coumaric acid. P-coumaric acid is an organic derivative of cinnamic acid, that carries a hydroxyl group at the 4-position of the benzene ring.
Polymers of unsubstituted phenoxy groups linked through ether bonds.
Polymers of unsubstituted phenoxy groups linked through thioether bonds.
Alkaloids extracted from the lupinus species. They usually possess a bi-, tri-, or tetracyclic skeleton consisting of one or more quinolizidine moieties.
Lupin alkaloids with a structure based on the matrine skeleton, a four-ring skeleton that based on a saturated dipyrido[2,1-f:3',2',1'-ij][1,6]naphthyridin-10-one skeleton.
Lupin alkaloids with a structure based on the lupinine skeleton, which is a bicyclic compound consisting of a quinolizidine.
Lupin alkaloids with a structure based on the cytisine skeleton, which is a tetracyclic ketone containing fused pyridine and piperidine rings that form pyrido[1,2a][1,5]diazocin-8-one.

Lupin alkaloids with a structure based on the anagyrine skeleton. Anagyrine is a tetracyclic ketone containing a quinolizidine, and two pyridine rings fused together to form dipyrido[1,2-a:1',2'-e][1,5]diazocin-4-one.

Alkaloids characterized by the presence of one or more alkylamino substituents attached to a steroidal skeleton. These are azasteroids in which a nitrogen atom forms an integral part of the steroid nucleus or may be present in the side chain.
Steroidal alkaloids with a structure that is characterized by a docosahydronaphth[2,1:4',5']indene ring system fused to a pyrano[3,2-b]pyridine moiety.

Alkaloids with a triterpenoid-steroid pregnane type structure with C-4 methyl groups, a 9beta,10beta-cycloartenol system, and a degraded C-20 side chain. Structurally, they are  derivatives of either a 9beta,10beta-cyclo-4,4,14alpha-trimethyl-5alpha-pregnane or a 9(10->19)abeo 4,4,14alpha-trimethyl-5alpha-pregnane system.
Alkaloids with a structure that is based on the samamine skeleton, a tetracyclic compound consisting of and azepane ring fuse a saturated cyclopenta[a]naphthalene derivative.
Steroidal alkaloids with a structure that is based on the jervane ring system. Jerveratrum alkaloids have alkamines with 1-3 oxygen atoms, and occur as such or as monoglycosides.

Steroidal alkaloids containing the cevane (23-methyl-4- azahexacyclo[12.11.0.0^{2,11}.0^{4,9}.0^{15,24}.0^{18,23}]pentacosane) moiety, which is a six ring system. Cerveratrum alkaloids have 7-9 oxygen atoms and occur as free alkamines or esters of simple aliphatic or aromatic acids.

Alkaloids with a structure based on the pregnane skeleton, which is characterized by the presence of monomethylamino or dimethylamino substituents either at C-3 and/or at the C-20 position in basic steroidal skeleton.
Alkaloids with a structure based on the conanine skeleton.
Steroid alkaloids obtained by reduction of spirosolane through opening of the E-ring.

Cholestane derivatives that contain the 22,23-secosolanidane moiety. 22,23-secosolanidane arises from the conversion of the  cholestane side-chain into a piperidine ring that is N-substituted with a 2-methylpropyl group.
Samamime-type alkaloids in which the A-ring of the steroidal backbone is an oxazolidine.
22,26-epiminocholestane derivatives carrying C=O group at the 3-position.
22,26-epicholestane derivatives carrying an amino group at the 3-position.
Spirostane derivatives carrying an amino group at the 3-position. Spirostanes are 16b,22:22,26-diepoxycholestanes, or 22,26-epoxyfurostans. The sixth ring so formed is known as ring F.
Diterpenoids with a structure based on the atisane skeleton, which is a tetracyclic compound containing the [2,2,2]bicyc1ic ring system with the C15-C16 bridge attached at C12.
Alkaloid diterpenoids with a structure based on the pentacyclic atisine skeleton.
Organic heterocyclic compounds containing a to furan rings fused to a central benzene ring. They can be grouped in angular and linear benzodifurans.
Benzodifurans containing angularly fused benzene and furan rings.
Benzodifurans containing linearly fused benzene and furan rings.
Alkaloids with a structure based on a tricyclic protopine formed by oxidative ring fission of protoberberine N-metho salts.
Alkaloids containing the vobasan skeleton.
Derivatives of lysergic acid are amides in which the amidic moiety is formed by a small peptide or an alkylamide.
Amides of Lysergic acids.
Hydroxy and dehydro derivatives of 6,8-dimethylergolenes and the corresponding ergolines.

Indole alkaloids with a structure based on the ibogamine skeleton or a derivative thereof. Ibogamine is a pentacyclic heterocyclic compound consisting of an indole fused to an azepane-containing tricyclic moiety ring. Iboga alkaloids arise from the cyclization of a secodine-type precursor through the formation of a 16,21 bond.
Alkaloids having a core structure based on the strychnan, stemmadenine (seco-curan), or the akuammicine (curan) skeleton.

Alkaloids with a structure based on the corynanthean nucleus, which is a tetracycle characterized by an indole fused to a quinolizidine. Additionally, the quinolizidine ring system is substituted to a 2-methylpropyl group and one ethyl group.

Alkaloids with a structure based on the vallesiachotaman skeleton. Vallesiachotaman is a tetracyclic compound that has a indolo[2,3-a]quinolizine core substituted by two methyl groups at the 3-, and 12-positions as well as a 2-methylbutane group at the 2-position.
Alkaloids containing the vincosan skeleton, a tetracyclic ring system containing a carboline and a tetrahydropyran ring.
Pyridoxines that carry a phosphate group at the 5-position.
Aromatic alcohols containing a 3-phenylprop-2-en-1-ol moiety.

Tryptophan-derived alkaloids that are derived from the fusion of tryptamine and a terpene unit (generally either 9 or 10 carbons). Aspidospermine and aspidospermidine (along with tabersonine) are the archetypical members of the Aspidosperma alkaloids.
Alkaloids with a dimeric chemical structure composed of an indole nucleus (catharanthine), and a dihydroindole nucleus (vindoline), joined together.

Alkaloids with a structure based on the quebrachamine skeleton, a tetracyclic compound that is derived by fission of the 7,21 bond of the aspidospermidine skeleton. Some quebrachamine alkaloids lack the C-16 methoxycarbonyl group.
Alkaloids with a structure based on the rhazinilam skeleton, a tetracyclic compound with a complex tetracyclic carbon skeleton containing pyrrole ring embedded in its indolizine core.

Alkaloids containing the pentacyclic tacaman skeleton, which consists of a pyrido[1,2-a]indole fused to a quinolizine. Tacaman alkaloids are obtained from a precursor to a pseudoaspidospermidine (type II skeleton) derivative, by the formation of new bonds at C-20/C-3 and C-140/C-17.
Amidines, in which the imino nitrogen is substituted by a hydroxy group.
Sulfobenzoic acid carrying the sulfonyl group at the 3-position of the benzene group.
Sulfobenzoic acid carrying the sulfonyl group at the 4-position of the benzene group.
Halophenols carrying a iodine on the benzene ring.
Halophenols carrying a bromine on the benzene ring.
Halophenols carrying a fluorine on the benzene ring.
Halophenols carrying a chlorine on the benzene ring.
Bromophenols carrying a iodine at the C3 position of the benzene ring.
Bromophenols carrying a iodine at the C2 position of the benzene ring.
Bromophenols carrying a iodine at the C4 position of the benzene ring.
Chlorophenols carrying a iodine at the C3 position of the benzene ring.
Chlorophenols carrying a iodine at the C2 position of the benzene ring.
Chlorophenols carrying a iodine at the C4 position of the benzene ring.
Fluorophenols carrying a iodine at the C3 position of the benzene ring.
Fluorophenols carrying a iodine at the C2 position of the benzene ring.
Fluorophenols carrying a iodine at the C4 position of the benzene ring.
Iodophenols carrying a iodine at the C3 position of the benzene ring.
Iodophenols carrying a iodine at the C2 position of the benzene ring.
Iodophenols carrying a iodine at the C4 position of the benzene ring.
Nitroquinoline derivative bearing a nitro group at ring position 4 and N-oxide group at ring position 1.
Erythrina alkaloids possessing either a 6-5-6-6-membered indoloisoquinoline core or a derivative thereof.
Erythrina alkaloids predominantly possessing a 6-5-7-6-membered indolobenzazepine skeleton or a derivative thereof.

Heterocyclic compounds containing a pyridine fused to a diazepine ring. Pyridine is 6-membered ring consisting of five carbon atoms and a nitrogen atom. Diazepine is a 7-membered ring consisting of five carbon atoms and two nitrogen centers.

Alkaloids with a structure based on either the akuammilan skeleton. The ring system in this group is formed from a precursor of the corynantheine type by bond formation between C-16 and C-7. Variations in this subgroup include, among others, alkaloids derived by C-3 to N-4 bond fission, as well as alkaloids in which the N-4 to C-5 bond in the Akuammiline skeleton has been severed.
Benzoic acids which bear a sulfanyl group (R-SH) attached to the benzene ring.
Compounds containing a benzene ring which bears a carboxyl group and a sulfhydryl functional group a positions 1 and 2, respectively.
Benzoic acids (or derivatives) which bear a sulfanyl group (R-SH) attached to the benzene ring at positions 1 and 3, respectively.
Benzoic acids (or derivatives) which bear a sulfanyl group (R-SH) attached to the benzene ring at positions 1 and 4, respectively.
Benzoic acids which bear a sulfanyl group (R-SH) attached to the benzene ring at positions 1 and 3, respectively.
Benzoic acids which bear a sulfanyl group (R-SH) attached to the benzene ring at positions 1 and 4, respectively.
Compounds contain an oxazinane ring with the nitrogen atom and the oxygen atom at positions 1  and 3, respectively.
Alkaloids with a structure based on the tricyclic acutumine skeleton, which contains an indoline moiety and two cyclopentene rings.
Alkaloids with a structure based on the hasubanan skeleton, a tetracyclic propellane.
Alkaloids with a structure based on the pavine skeleton.
Alkaloids with a structure based on the isopavine skeleton.
Organic compounds containing a carbon-boron bond.
Triazinanes having three nitrogen ring atoms at the 1-, 2-, and 3- positions.
Triazinanes having three nitrogen ring atoms at the 1-, 2-, and 4- positions.
Triazinanes having three nitrogen ring atoms at the 1-, 3-, and 5- positions.
Organosulfur compounds with the general formula RSSSR' (R,R'=alkyl, aryl).
Organosulfur compounds with the general formula RSSR' (R,R' = alkyl, aryl).
Quinones with a structure characterized by the hydroquinone ring substituted by an prenyl side-chain.
Quinones with a structure characterized by the quinone ring substituted by an prenyl side-chain.
Organic compounds containing a thianthrene moiety. Thianthrene is a tricyclic ring system that consists of two benzene rings fused to each other through a 1,4-dithiin ring.
Organic heterocyclic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to a dithiin ring. Dithiin is an unsaturated six-member heterocycle containing four carbon atoms, two sulfur atoms and two double bonds.
Organic heterocyclic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to a 1,2-dithiin ring.
Organic heterocyclic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to a 1,3-dithiin ring.
Organic heterocyclic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to a 1,4-dithiin ring.
Organic heterocyclic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to a 2,3-dithiin ring.
Organic heterocyclic compounds containing a N-methylated pyrrole.
Amides of cinnamic acids. Cinnamic acid is an aromatic compound containing a benzene and a carboxylic acid group forming 3-phenylprop-2-enoic acid.
Organic compounds containing a phenylpropane moiety.

Carbohydrate derivatives containing glucuronic acid linked to another substance through an ester bond attached at position C-1, C-2, C-3, or C-4 of the glucuronic acid moiety. The C-1 acyl glucuronide is usually the initial isomer, However, the acyl group can rearrange from its initial position on the C-1 hydroxyl group of the glucuronic acid moiety to the C-2 and, subsequently, the C-3 and the C-4 hydroxyl group. Formation of the C-3 from the C-2 isomer, and the C-4 from the C-3 isomer is possible, whereas the C-1 isomer cannot result from the other regioisomers via acyl migration.
Glucuronides in which the aglycone is linked to the carbohydrate unit through an O-glycosidic bond.
Glucuronides in which the aglycone is linked to the carbohydrate unit through a N-glycosidic bond.
Glucuronides in which the aglycone is linked to the carbohydrate unit through a C-glycosidic bond.
Carbohydrate derivatives containing glucuronic acid linked to another substance through a S-glycosidic bond.
Organic heterocyclic compounds with a structure containing a dibenzopyran moiety, made up of two benzene rings fused to a central pyran ring.
Organic heterocyclic compounds with a structure containing a dibenzothiophene moiety, made up of two benzene rings fused to a central thiophene ring.
Flavonoids with a structure based on the 3-phenylchromene skeleton, with a double bond between the C3 and C4 carbon atoms of the chromene moiety.
Flavonoids with a structure based on an isoflav-3-ene skeleton bearing an oxo-group at position C2.
Isoflavones where the atoms C-2 and C-3 are both linked to the same oxygen atom to form an epoxide ring.
Lupin alkaloids with a structure based on the leontidine skeleton, a tetracyclic compound containing fused piperidine, pyridine, and pyrrolidine rings.

Lupin Alkaloids with a structure based on the aloperine skeleton. Aloperine is a tetracyclic compound made up of a quinolizidine and a decahydroquinoline joined to  form 3,15-diazatetracycloheptadecane.

Alkaloids with a structure based on the perhydro-9b-azaphenalene skeleton. Perhydro-9b-azaphenalene is a tricyclic compound consisting of quinolizidine that share its only nitrogen atom with a piperidine. In some 9b-azaphenalenes, the resulting tricyclic backbone can be unsaturated.
Aloperine alkaloids with a structure based on the ormosanine skeleton.
Compounds containing a pyrido[2,3,4-kl]acridine carrying a C=O group.
Organic heterocyclic compounds with a structure based on the pyrido[2,3,4-kl]acridine skeleton.
Organic heterocyclic compounds with a structure based on the Pyrrolo[2,3,4-kl]acridine skeleton.
Organic heterocyclic compounds with a structure based on the Pyrrolo[4,3,2-de]quinoline skeleton.
Psoralens containing a hydroxyl group attached at the C5 position of the psoralen group.
Psoralens containing a hydroxyl group attached at the C8 position of the psoralen group.
Psoralens containing a methoxy group attached at the C5 position of the psoralen group.
Psoralens containing a methoxy group attached at the C8 position of the psoralen group.
Organic heterocyclic compounds containing a thiochromane moiety.
Organic heterocyclic compounds containing an isothiochromane moiety.
Organic heterocyclic compounds containing a pyrazolidinone moiety.
Organic compounds made up only of carbon and hydrogen atoms.

Acyclic and cyclic hydrocarbons having one or more carbon-carbon double bonds, apart from the formal ones in aromatic compounds. The class of olefins subsumes alkenes and cycloalkenes and the corresponding polyenes.
Olefins that do not contain a ring in their structure.
Olefins that contain at least one ring in their structure.
Acyclic hydrocarbons that contain exactly three carbon-to-carbon double bonds.
Acyclic hydrocarbons that contain exactly four carbon-to-carbon double bonds.
Acyclic (branched or unbranched) and cyclic (with or without side chain) hydrocarbons having one or more carbon to carbon triple bonds.
Acyclic branched or unbranched hydrocarbons having two triple bonds, with the general formula CnH2n-6.
Acyclic branched or unbranched hydrocarbons having three triple bonds, with the general formula CnH2n-10.
Cyclic hydrocarbons containing one or more acetylene groups.
Acyclic hydrocarbons containing one or more acetylene groups.
Monocyclic hydrocarbons containing one or more acetylene groups.
Polycyclic hydrocarbons containing one or more acetylene groups.
Unsaturated monocyclic hydrocarbons having one endocyclic triple bond.
Quinones that carry an imine group.
Cytochalasans in which the hydrogenated isoindolone bears a benzyl group.
Compounds with a structure containing an aziridines ring bearing one carbonyl group. They are cyclic amides of acetic acid.
Cyclic amides of carboximidic acids. Lactams are tautomers of lactams, having an endocyclic carbon-nitrogen double bond.
Compounds having two beta-haloalkyl groups bound to a phosphorus atom.
Alcohols in which two hydroxy groups are bonded to the same atom.
Organophosphorus compounds with the general formula RNP(O)(O)=O (R=alkyl, aryl).

Oxazaphospholanes containing the isofamide skeleton. Isofamide is a heterocyclic compound made up of a 1,3,2-oxazaphospholane, where the phosphorus atom is part of a phosphodiamide group, and the oxazaphospholane is substituted by two haloalkyl chains.
Oxazol-5(4H)-ones I, compounds derived by cyclization of N-acyl alpha-amino carboxylic acids, RC(=O)NHCR2C(=O)OH, through formal loss of the elements of water.
Compounds having the general structure RN=S(=O)2.
Vinyl halides in which a fluorine atom is bonded to an sp2-hybridised carbon atom.
Vinyl halides in which a iodine atom is bonded to an sp2-hybridised carbon atom.
Vinyl halides in which a chlorine atom is bonded to an sp2-hybridised carbon atom.
Vinyl halides in which a bromine atom is bonded to an sp2-hybridised carbon atom.
Organic compounds with the general structure RC(=O)X, where X is a halogen atom.
Organic compounds containing an aromatic ring (or ring system) carrying a C-X bond.
Organic compounds containing a linear aliphatic chain (or ring system) carrying a C-X bond, where X is a halogen atom.
Organic compounds in which the halogen atom is bonded to an sp2-hybridised carbon atom of a carbon-carbon double bond (C=C).
Organic compounds containing the sulfuryl halide group.
Organic compounds containing the imidoyl halide functional group, with the general structure R(X)C=NR' (R, R'=H, alkyl, aryl; X = halogen).

Diterpenoids containing a skeleton based on or derived from the ent-kaurane moiety. Grayanoids usually possess either one of the grayanane, the 2,4-seco-grayanane, the 9,10-seco-grayanane, the 1,5-seco-grayanane, the kalmane, or the leucothane skeleton. Some derivatives also include the 1,5-seco-kalmane skeleton.

Sesquiterpenoids with a structure based on the elemane skeleton. Elemane is a monocyclic compound consisting of a cyclohexane ring substituted with a methyl group, an ethyl group, and two 1-methylethyl groups at the 1-, 1-, 2-, and 4-position, respectively.
Sesquiterpenoids with a structure based on the pseudoguaiane skeleton, which arises by the migration of the a methyl group of the bicyclic guaiane skeleton from the C4 to the C5 position.

Sesquiterpenoids with a structure based on the guaiane skeleton. Guaiane is a bicyclic compound consisting of a decahydroazulene moiety, substituted with two methyl groups and a 1-methylethyl group at the 1-, 4-, and 7-position, respectively.

Diterpenoids containing the tigliane or ingenane carbon skeleton. The tigliane skeleton is a tetracyclic ring that consists of the 4/7/6/3 ring junction. It is derived from casbane by 6,10- and 5,14-cyclizations and is a framework of phorbol. The ingenane skeleton is derived by rearrangement of tigliane.
Fungal diterpenoid metabolites with a structure containing the cyathane skeleton (Tetradecahydro-3a,5a,8-trimethyl-1-(1-methylethyl)-cyclohept[e]indene).

Diterpenoids with a structure based on the jatrophane or the 9,13-jatrophane skeleton. Jatrophane can be derived from casbane by 6,10-cyclization and opening of the cyclopropane. Cyclojatrophane diterpenoids are based on the 9,13-cyclization of the jatrophane skeleton yields the 9,13-cyclojatrophane skeleton.
Diterpenoids with a structure based either on the leucothol or the grayanotoxane skeleton.
Diterpenoids with a structure based either on the xeniaphyllane or the xenicane skeleton.
Diterpenoids containing a sphaerane skeleton or tetradecahydro-5,8a,10a-trimethyl-1-(1-methylethyl)-phenanthrene.

Sesterterpnoids with a structure based on the cheilanthane backbone. Cheilanthane is a tricyclic compound consisting of a tetradecahydrophenanthrene ring system that carries two methyl groups at the 1-position, one methyl group at the 4a-,7-, and 8a-positions, as well as a 3-methylpentyl group at the 8-position.

Sesterterpnoids with a structure based on the ophiobolane backbone. Ophiobolane is a tricyclic compound consisting of two cyclopentane rings joined by a cyclooctane ring, and carries a methyl group at the 1-, 4-, and 8-position, as well as a 6-methylheptane group at the 12-position.

Sesterterpenoids with a structure based on the scalarane backbone. Scalarane is a tetracyclic compound, which is similar the homoandrostane with five methyl groups at the 4-, 4-, 8-, 17-, 17a-positions.
Triterpenoids with a structure based on the lupane skeleton. They arise from the formation of a five membered ring E from the baccharane precursor.
Triterpenoids with a structure based either on the tirucallane or the euphane skeleton. They are obtained by backbone rearrangement of a dammarane-based precursor.
Triterpenoids with a structure based on either the taraxastane, ursane, or bauerane skeleton. These are obtained by methyl migration in ring E of the oleanane backbone.

column2: Taraxerane, multiflorane, glutinane and friedelane triterpenoids
column3: Triterpenoids with a structure based either on the taraxerane, the multiflorane, the glutinane, or the friedelane skeleton. These compounds arise upon rearrangement of the oleanane skeleton.
Triterpenoids with a structure based on the dammarane skeleton.
Triterpenoids with a structure based either on the protostane or the fusidane skeleton.
Marine diterpenoids with a structure based on the briarane (3,8-cyclocembrane) skeleton.
Inorganic compounds in which the largest oxoanion is metavanadate, and in which the heaviest atom not in an oxoanion is an actinide.
Imines derived from quinones by replacement of one or both oxygens by =NR.
Quinonimines in which the imine groups are in a meta-relationship.
Quinonimines in which the imine groups are in a ortho-relationship.
Quinonimines in which the imine groups are in a para-relationship.
C-glycosylated derivatives of isoflavonoids, which are natural products derived from 3-phenylchromen-4-one.
5-O-glycosylated neoflavonoids. Neoflavonoids are compounds with a structure based on the 4-phenylchromene backbone.
Homoisoflavonoids with a structure based on the chromanone system. Chromanone is a bicyclic compound consisting of a 3,4-dihydro-1-benzopyran, which bears a ketone group at the 4-position.
Organic acids with the general formula RS(=NN)OOH.
Flavonoids with a structure based on the 1,2-diaryl-2-propen-1-ol skeleton.
Flavonoids with a structure based on the 3-phenylchromene skeleton, with a double bond between the C2 and C3 carbon atoms of the chromene moiety.

A group of macrolides with a structure containing a 16-membered lactone ring fused to a 1,7-dioxaspiroundecane ring system and to either a benzofuran (or hydrogenated derivative thereof). In some cases (e.g. Milbemycin E), the tetrahydrofuranyl ring is missing. Milbemycins can be o-glycosylated at C13 to form Avermectins. Milbemycins are produced by Streptomyces species.
Heterocyclic compounds characterized by  two 8-hydroxy-1,4-dihydronaphthalen-1-one moieties joined together one or two CC-bonds.
Steroids with a structure characterized by a lanostane moiety possessing a 18,20-lactone ring.
Organic heterocyclic compounds containing a 1,2-dithiole ring that bears a C=S group.
Tigliane diterpenoids which are esters of phorbol.
Coumarins that contain one or more hydroxyl groups attached to C4-position the coumarin skeleton.
Coumarins that contain one or more hydroxyl groups attached to the coumarin skeleton.
Coumarins that contain one or more hydroxyl groups attached to the C7 position the coumarin skeleton.
Organic heterocyclic compounds containing a saturated aliphatic six-membered ring consisting of five carbon atoms and one boron atom.
Triterpenoids with a structure based either on the polypodane, the malabaricane, or the podiodane skeleton.
Organic compounds containing a carboxylic acid, and an amine group attached to the alpha carbon atom, relative to the C=O group.
Ketones containing a hydroxyl group attached to the beta-carbon atom, relative to the C=O group.
Flavonoids that bear one hydroxyl group at the C-3 position of the flavonoid skeleton.
Flavonoids that bear one hydroxyl group at the C-3' position of the flavonoid skeleton.
Diterpenoids with a structure based on either the eunicellane (5,14-cyclocembrane) or the asbestinane skeleton.
Triterpenoids with a structure based on the arborinane or stictane skeleton.
Triterpenoids with a structure based either on the serratane or the onocerane skeleton.
Compounds containing a phenyl group linked to a tropane moiety. Tropane is an organonitrogenous  [3.2.1] bicyclic organic compound.
Compounds containing a diazepane rings, which is a saturated seven-membered ring with 2 nitrogen atoms and five carbon atoms.
Diazepanes having the two nitrogen atoms at position 1 and 2 of the diazepane ring.
Diazepanes having the two nitrogen atoms at position 1 and 3 of the diazepane ring.
Diazepanes having the two nitrogen atoms at position 1 and 4 of the diazepane ring.
Compounds containing an oxadiazole ring with the oxygen and the two nitrogen atoms at positions 1, 2, and 4, respectively.
Compounds containing an oxadiazole ring with the oxygen and the two nitrogen atoms at positions 1, 3, and 4, respectively.
Compounds having the general structure RC(OR')3 ( R' not H), or the structure C(OR')4 ( R' not H).
Hypothetical  Compounds having the general structure RC(NH2)3, and N-substituted derivatives thereof.
Ortho acid derivatives of carboxylic acids, with the general formula RC(OH)3.
Organic derivatives of sulfimide, with the general formula RN=S(R=organic group).
Diterpenoids with a structure based on the mutilane skeleton.
Diterpenoids with a structure based on the aphidicolane or the stemodane  skeleton.
Isoquinoline derivatives carrying one C=O group at positions 1, and 3 respectively.
Isoquinoline derivatives carrying a C=O group at positions 1 and 4, respectively.
Phenolic compounds containing a flavonoid moiety which is O-glycosidically linked to glucuronic acid.
7-O-glycosylated neoflavonoids. Neoflavonoids are compounds with a structure based on the 4-phenylchromene backbone.
Organic heterocyclic compounds containing a cycloheptane derivative fused to a furan. Furan is a five-membered aromatic ring with four carbon atoms and one oxygen atom.

Organic heterocyclic compounds containing a cycloheptane derivative fused to a pyran. Pyran a six-membered heterocyclic, non-aromatic ring, made up of five carbon atoms and one oxygen atom and containing two double bonds.
Compounds containing a cyclopentane ring that carries an alcohol group.
Compounds containing a dioxepane ring, which is a seven-membered aliphatic unsaturated ring with two oxygen atoms and five carbon atoms.
Dioxepines with the two ring oxygen atoms at position 1 and 2, respectively.
Dioxepines with the two ring oxygen atoms at position 1 and 3, respectively.
Dioxepines with the two ring oxygen atoms at position 1 and 4, respectively.
Compounds containing a dioxepane ring, which is a seven-membered aliphatic saturated ring with two oxygen atoms and five carbon atoms.
Dioxepanes with the two ring oxygen atoms at position 1 and 2, respectively.
Dioxepanes with the two ring oxygen atoms at position 1 and 3, respectively.
Dioxepanes with the two ring oxygen atoms at position 1 and 4, respectively.
Aromatic compounds containing a guanidine group linked to the benzene ring of a benzoic acid.
Benzoic acids containing an amine group attached to the benzene moiety.
Fatty acids with an aliphatic tail that contains between 13 and 21 carbon atoms.
Fatty acids with an aliphatic tail that contains at least 22 carbon atoms.
Fatty alcohols that have an aliphatic tail of 13 to 21 carbon atoms.
Fatty aldehydes carrying a long aliphatic chain, with 13 to 21 carbon atoms.
Organic compounds containing a sulfonamide group linked to a piperidine ring.
Heterocyclic compounds based on the 5,6,7,8-tetrahydropteroic acid skeleton conjugated with at least one L-glutamic acid unit.
Tetrahydrogenated isoquinoline derivatives.
Compounds containing a phenyl group attached to the C1-atom of a tetrahydroisoquinoline moiety.
Compounds containing a phenyl group attached to the C4-atom of a tetrahydroisoquinoline moiety.
Isoquinoline derivatives where exactly two carbon atoms joined by an aromatic bond are linked with a hydrogen atom each, resulting in a CC single bond.
Organic compounds with the general formula RS(=O)(=O)NHNH2.
Organic compounds containing a 3-hydroxyl acylated coenzyme A derivative.
Sphingolipids containing a N-acylated sphingosine.
Sphingolipids containing a N-acylated sphinganine.
N-acylated 4-hydroxysphinganine.
Compounds containing an alpha amino acid which bears a formyl group at its terminal nitrogen atom.
Compounds containing an alpha amino acid (or a derivative thereof) which bears a formyl group at its terminal nitrogen atom.
Carboxylic acids containing exactly four carboxyl groups.
Carboxylic acids containing exactly six carboxyl groups.

Waxes based on  beta-hydroxy acids (usually C8 to C16) esterified with s fatty acid (usually C6 to C16) at the beta-hydroxy position and with  a fatty alcohol (usually C16 to C20) at the carboxyl group.
Waxes based on alkane-1,2-diols (usually C12-C23) esterified with C10-C20 acids at the two hydroxyl groups.

Organic heterocyclic compounds consisting of a thieno[3,4-d]pyridazine moiety. Thieno[3,4-d]pyridazine is a bicyclic compound made up of a thiophene ring fused to a pyridazine ring so that the sulfur atom and the two nitrogen atoms are at the 1-, 4-, and 5-position, respectively.

Organic compounds containing a thieno[3,4-c]pyridazine that carries an amino group at the 2-position. Thieno[3,4-c]pyridazine is a bicyclic compound made up of a thiophene ring fused to a pyridazine ring so that the sulfur atom and the two nitrogen atoms are at the 1-, 5-, and 6-position, respectively.

Organic compounds containing a thieno[3,4-d]pyridazine that carries an amino group at the 2-position. Thieno[3,4-d]pyridazine is a bicyclic compound made up of a thiophene ring fused to a pyridazine ring so that the sulfur atom and the two nitrogen atoms are at the 1-, 4-, and 5-position, respectively.

Steroid compounds that carry a carboxyl group at the C3-atom of the steroid backbone.

Organonitrogen compounds with the formula RN(R')N or R[N+](R')N-, where R and R' are organic groups.
Organic compounds containing a 1,2-dithiolane ring. 1,2-dithiolane moiety is a 5-membered  saturated aliphatic ring with three carbon atoms, and two sulfur atoms at the 1- and 2- ring positions.
Organic compounds containing a 1,3-dithiolane ring. 1,3-dithiolane moiety is a 5-membered saturated aliphatic ring with three carbon atoms, and two sulfur atoms at the 1- and 3- ring positions.

Organic compounds containing a 1,2-dithiolane ring that bears one or more carboxylic acid groups. The 1,2-dithiolane moiety is a 5-membered ring with three carbon atoms, and two sulfur atoms at the 1- and 2- ring positions.

Organic compounds containing a 1,3-dithiolane ring that bears one or more carboxylic acid groups. The 1,3-dithiolane moiety is a 5-membered ring with three carbon atoms, and two sulfur atoms at the 1- and 3- ring positions.

Organic compounds containing the thiophosphoric acid functional group or a derivative thereof, with the general structure ROP(OR')(OR'')=S, where exactly one R-group is an organyl group.

S-ester derivatives of dithiophosphates, with the general structure RSP(O)(O)=S (R = organyl group).
Glycerophospholipids in which the O1 and O3 oxygen atoms of the central glycerol moiety are each linked to one 1-monoacylglyerol chain.
Glycerophospholipids that contain three glycerol moieties sequentially linked to each other with a phosphate group. They include cardiolipins.
Sphingoid analogue of phosphatidic acid formed from ceramide by adding a phosphate group at its 1-position.
Sphingolipids with a structure based on a sphingoid base that is attached to a phosphonate head group. They differ from Phosphosphingolipids which have a phosphate head group.
Sphingolipids with a structure based on a sphingoid base that is attached to a phosphate head group. They differ from phosphonospingolipids which have a phosphonate head group.
Dinucleotides where the two bases are connected via a (2'->5')-phosphodiester linkage.
Dinucleotides where the two bases are connected via a (3'->5')-phosphodiester linkage.

(3'->5')-dinucleotides in which one of the based bears a phosphate group (or a phosphate chain) at the 5'-position.

Diterpenoids with a structure characterized by a sphenolobane skeleton. They possess a trans-fused hydroazulenoid skeleton as a common structural motif, but differ in configuration at C(9), where a prenyl group is attached. Sphenolobane is also considered an 'extended' daucane skeleton, with a carbon side chain appended onto the cyclopentane ring.

column2: Amphilectane, neoamphilectane, cycloamphilectane, and adociane diterpenoids
column3: Diterpenoids with a structure based on the amphilectane or a seco-,neo-, or cyclo- derivative thereof. Amphilectane is a tricyclic structure made up of three cyclohexane fused together, with a methyl group at the C11-, C7-, and C3- positions. Additionally, it carries a 2-methylpropyl group at the C1-position. Amphilectanes are presumably derived from serrulatanes. Cycloamphilectanes represent a further cyclisation.
Sesterterpenoids with a structure containing a cyclohexane linked to an isoprenyl chain. They arise by cyclisation of the acyclic sesterterpene skeleton between carbons 14 and 19.

Diterpenoids with a structure characterized by a stemarane skeleton. Some characteristics include the bicyclic system C/D that is constituted by a bicyclo[3.2.1]octane fused to the bicyclic A/B system in a different fashion with respect to other tetracyclic diterpenes possessing the bicyclo[3.2.1]octane system. Moreover, the two contiguous quaternary carbon atoms,  C(9) and C(10), are present, the former being a spirocyclic atom. Oxygenation can happen at positions C(2), C(7), C(13), C(17), C(18), and C(19).

column2: Villanovane, atisane, trachylobane or helvifulvane diterpenoids
column3: Diterpenoids with a structure based on the villanovane, atisane, trachylobane or helvifulvane skeleton. The astisane and atisane skeletons arise from the rearrangement of the beyerane cation intermediate. The trachylobane and helvifulvane skeletons are formed by rearrangement of the beyerane cation intermediate followed by cyclisation.
Lipids with a structure containing a glycerol moiety linked at its  terminal C3 atom to a N-methylphosphoethanolamine group, and at its C1 and C2 terminal atoms by an acyl group.
Lipids with a structure containing a glycerol moiety linked at its  terminal C3 atom to a N,N-dimethylphosphoethanolamine group, and at its C1 and C2 terminal atoms by an acyl group.

Glycerophospholipids where the central glycerol is acylated at the 1- and 2-positions by two acyl chains, and is linked at the 3-position to a phosphoethanol.  They are phospholipids formed only in the presence of ethanol via the action of phospholipase D.
Phenylpropanoids containing the 2-phenylbenzofuran moiety.
Isoflavonoids that bear a ketone group at the C2-position.
Flavonoid compounds with a structure based on the isochromeno[4,3-b]-chromene skeleton. This skeleton results from the fusion of an isochromene to a chromene ring system.
Organic aromatic compounds containing an isobenzofuran moiety.
Compounds containing a 2-benzofuran moiety that carries an oxo group at the 1 position.

Organic aromatic compounds that 1-benzopyran, a bicyclic compound made up of a benzene ring fused to a pyran, so that the oxygen atom is at the 2-position.

Organic heterocyclic compounds containing a benzene ring fused to a pyran ring. Pyran a six-membered heterocyclic, non-aromatic ring, made up of five carbon atoms and one oxygen atom and containing two double bonds.
Organic aromatic compounds that 1-benzothiopyran, a bicyclic compound made up of a benzene ring fused to a thiopyran, so that the sulfur atom is at the 1-position.
Organic aromatic compounds that 1-benzothiopyran, a bicyclic compound made up of a benzene ring fused to a thiopyran, so that the sulfur atom is at the 2-position.
Polyketides with a structure based on then benz[a]anthracene skeleton, with the particularity that the central ring of the anthracene moiety is a para-quinone.
Organic compounds containing a carboxyl group that is esterified with a methyl group. They have the general structure RC(=O)OR', where R=H or organyl group and R'=methyl group.
Compounds containing a fatty acid that is esterified with a methyl group. They have the general structure RC(=O)OR', where R=fatty aliphatic tail or organyl group and R'=methyl group.

Neolignans in which the two C6-C3 units are linked together by a bond other than Cbeta-Cbeta'. They usually consist of a 1-benzofuran or 2,3-dihydro-1-benzofuran, which is substituted a the 2-, 3-, and 5-positions with a phenyl group, a methyl group, and a propyl group, respectively.
Lignans with a structure characterized by to phenylpropanoid units coupled together through the C7-C7' and C8-C8' bonds, forming a cyclobutane ring with the C7, C7', C8', and C8 atoms.
Ketones that have an acyloxy substituent alpha to the carbonyl group. They have the general structure R4C(=O)OC(R2)(R3)C(R1)=O (R1=organyl, R4=H or organyl; R2,R3 = any atom).

Lignans that contain either isomer of the 7,8'-epoxylignan skeleton. The first isomer consists of a tetrahydrofuran that carries a phenyl group at the 2- and the 4-positions, as well as one a methyl group at the 3- and 5-positions. The second isomer consists of a tetrahydrofuran that carries a benzyl group, a phenyl group, and a methyl group at the 2-, 4-, 5-position, respectively.
Lignans that contain the 7,9'-epoxylignan skeleton, which consists of a tetrahydrofuran that carries a phenyl group, a methyl group, and a benzyl group at the 2-, 3-, 4-position, respectively.
Lignans with a structure based on a 2,5-diaryl-3, 4-dimethyltetrahydrofuran skeleton.

Lignans with a structure based on the 9,9'-epoxylignan skeleton, which consists of a tetrahydrofuran that carries two benzyl groups at the 3- and 4-positions. Additionally they are oxygenated at the 2-position to form dibenzylbutyrolactones (oxo group) or a dibenzylbutyrolactols (hydroxyl group).
Lignans with a structure based on the 1-phenyltetralin skeleton.
Lignans with a structure based on the 1-phenyltetralin skeleton carrying a hydroxyl group at the 9- and the 9'- position.

Alkaloids are characterized by a pyrrolo[1,2- a]azepine nucleus usually linked with two carbon chains mostly forming terminal lactone rings. They can be clasified in different subgroups, based on the different carbon chains attached to C-9 of the pyrroloazepine nucleus.

Stemona alkaloids with a structure containing a pyrrolo[1,2-a]azepine group, where the azepine moiety forms a spiro system with oxolane-5-one to give spiro[oxolane-2,9'-pyrrolo[1,2-a]azepine]-5-one. Moreover, another 5-oxooxolane moiety attached to the pyrrole ring.

Stemona alkaloids with a structure that typically contains a 3-methyloxolan-2-one and a 5-propyloxolan-2-one moieties that are attached to the characteristic pyrrolo[1,2-a]azepine skeleton at the C3 and C9 position, respectively.

Stemona alkaloids with a structure containing a pyrrolo[1,2-a]azepine skeleton (S1) , one 5-oxooxolane moiety (S2), and one a 5-(oxolan-2-yl)oxolan-2-one moiety (S3). The S2 moiety is linked to the C3 atom of the pyrrole ring in the S1 moiety. Additionally, the azepine ring of S1 is fused to one oxolane ring of the S3 moiety.
Alkaloids with a structure that is based on the vallesaman skeleton, a tetracyclic compound that contains a piperidine ring fused to an indole.

Compounds containing a pyrrolidine moiety that is substituted at the N1-position with an alkyl group. Pyrrolidine is a five-membered saturated aliphatic heterocycle with one nitrogen atom and four carbon atoms.
L-isomers of N-acyl-homoserine-lactones.

Compounds containing a purine that carries a thiol group at the 6-position. Purine is a bicyclic aromatic compound made up of a pyrimidine ring fused to an imidazole ring.
Compounds that contain an alkylamine group attached at the 6-position of a purine. Purine is a bicyclic aromatic compound made up of a pyrimidine ring fused to an imidazole ring.

Organic heterocyclic compounds containing a thiolane ring that carries a thione group at the 2-position. Thiolane is a five-membered saturated aliphatic ring made up of one sulfur atom and four carbon atoms.

Organic heterocyclic compounds containing a thiolane ring that carries a thione group at the 3-position. Thiolane is a five-membered saturated aliphatic ring made up of one sulfur atom and four carbon atoms.

Organic aromatic compounds that contain a p-dioxole ring that is angularly fused to the benzene ring of a coumarin. In p-dioxolo[2,3-h]coumarins, the coumarin ring system shares its C7-C8 bond with the p-dioxole ring.

Non-conventional lignans that derived from stilbene. They are characterized by a p-dioxin ring substituted at one carbon atom by a C3C6 (phenylpropan) group and fused to one ring of the stilbene moiety.
